70afb4a5893383bd	normal	The four hundred ninety three outbreaks reported during this period resulted in at least twenty seven thousand two hundred nineteen illnesses and eight deaths.
dba79253e5668864	normal	The number of respiratory disease outbreaks increased over time and skin infection outbreaks decreased over time.
522a26eebb2c2dcd	normal	Diarrheal disease outbreaks caused by Cryptosporidium leveled off during two thousand eight through twenty fourteen.
415769e234c75d4c	normal	More than half of outbreaks started in the summer, the peak season for swimming.
8c42776e7de11504	normal	Common parasite remains the leading cause of illness from pools.
090665cb7d239a29	normal	Crypto causes fifty eight percent of outbreaks where a germ was identified linked to pools, hot tubs, and water playgrounds and eighty nine percent of the illnesses.
561287d71e227e64	normal	Crypto spreads in pools when someone sick with the parasite has diarrhea in the water and other swimmers swallow that contaminated water.
00958864fdb5a2a5	normal	Swimmers and parents of young swimmers play an essential role in preventing Crypto outbreaks.
c37d30b66d1b8347	normal	Swallowing just a mouthful of water with Crypto in it can make otherwise healthy kids and adults sick for weeks with watery diarrhea, stomach cramps, nausea, and vomiting.
f0938af7b0e3eaf3	normal	Don't go into the water, and don't let your kids go into the water, if sick with diarrhea.
21f68eb9e0584d27	normal	Bacteria cause respiratory illness and skin rashes.
de5b74778dcdd3c7	normal	The bacteria Legionella and Pseudomonas are the next most leading causes of these outbreaks, with sixteen percent of outbreaks caused by Legionella and thirteen percent caused by Pseudomonas.
941dcf9736946401	normal	Legionella can cause severe pneumonia and symptoms similar to the flu.
b718e0c6924567d6	normal	Pseudomonas can cause hot tub rash and swimmer's ear.
9d499838b2b9904d	normal	If a pool, hot tub, or water playground is not cleaned properly, bacteria can grow and form a slime called biofilm on wet surfaces.
d576c5671c4d192a	normal	It is harder for disinfectants to kill these bacteria when they are protected by biofilm.
f7d457cc86ae98a9	normal	Pool operators need to maintain proper cleaning practices and disinfectant levels to prevent bacteria from growing and causing illnesses in swimmers.
97db784b798d5181	normal	C.D.C. provides specific recommendations for operating public pools, hot tubs and water playgrounds in the Model Aquatic Health Code.
ee2c558c004aa31c	normal	Some people are more likely to get sick, including people fifty years or older, current or former smokers, people with chronic lung disease, and people with a weakened immune system.
33888829b5916e89	normal	These people should see a doctor right away if they develop pneumonia symptoms and let the doctor know about any possible exposures, including recent hot tub use.
6b3873e6c5375ea2	normal	Protect yourself and your family from germs spread through the water we swim in and share.

cfa9a3e8592aeec3	normal	Don't swim or let your kids swim if sick with diarrhea. Wait until two weeks after diarrhea has stopped to go swimming.

a351c0717f400b20	normal	A new rabies test could mean people exposed to potentially rabid animals could forego the weeks-long regimen of shots to prevent the deadly disease.
19f2901496cb7938	normal	The new test, designed for use in animals, can more easily and precisely diagnose rabies infection, according to a study published today in P.L.O.S. One.
649600c55e1a1fc8	normal	The new L.N. thirty four test is simpler and easier to use than current tests.
be2a3eac7ae5ba20	normal	During the pilot study, it produced no false negatives, fewer false positive, and fewer inconclusive results.
190e8e3331746139	normal	It could allow doctors and patients to make better informed decisions about who needs treatment for rabies, which is nearly always fatal once symptoms start.
744e4041e39559bd	normal	The test can also be run on testing platforms already widely used in the U.S. and worldwide, without any extra training.
aaea7665196fd77e	normal	And it yields results even from decomposing animal brain tissue.
a333797e9df82e06	normal	The current gold-standard for rabies testing in animals is the direct fluorescent antibody test.
91b2ca6aea4e5cb6	normal	It can only be interpreted by laboratory workers with special skills, extensive training, and a specific type of microscope.
cf8d4e0514361630	normal	The new test could help improve rabies testing in the United States and in resource-poor countries.
46543992eee97288	normal	Currently, testing facilities in many countries in Africa and Asia most affected by rabies are not able to easily rule out the disease in animals that have bitten someone. In these countries, equipment for testing and rabies vaccine supplies are often held in centralized urban areas, several days' travel from where someone is bitten.
dc80f9044b20f640	normal	Rabies vaccine can cost several months' salary, so knowing if an animal that bit someone is rabid is valuable information.
0a88ba01207fc4ac	normal	Many of the areas hardest hit by rabies are also the areas least prepared to run current tests to diagnose it, said Crystal Gigante, a microbiologist.
f3fde101886b24c4	normal	The L.N. thirty four test has the potential to really change the playing field.
676e9c7dee14d7ba	normal	Quickly knowing who needs to receive rabies treatment, and who does not, will save lives and families' livelihoods.
9bff3d5c8e5e6b5b	normal	In the recent study, staff at fourteen labs worldwide assessed nearly three thousand animal brain samples from the Americas, Europe, Africa, and Asia.
daddf78ec94e0972	normal	More than one thousand were known to be infected with rabies virus.
b8d275c4d60506e2	normal	The samples came from more than sixty mammal species that get rabies, including dogs, raccoons, skunks, foxes, and bats.
1d51b83f8db34987	normal	It correctly identified all D.F.A. positive samples as positive.
15a7fe0e228f375c	normal	In addition, it produced definitive findings for eighty samples that were inconclusive or untestable by the D.F.A. test
4adecf902f180915	normal	Twenty nine of those were positive for rabies.
501bb75dc26c52db	normal	Of the three thousand samples tested, it identified one false negative and eleven false positive D.F.A. test results.
c34e800f32ca0e07	normal	Only one sample was indeterminate using both tests.
0c463f97d196d211	normal	This study is the largest ever to validate usage of this type of test (a real-time R.T. P.C.R.) to diagnose rabies in animals.
fe5a9b107586870c	normal	New Rabies Test: Greater Flexibility.
9faa42622e8b68c5	normal	L.N. thirty four testing uses P.C.R., a testing platform that labs worldwide already use to test for flu, H.I.V., and tuberculosis.
7d3e7bb2797aa28b	normal	In contrast, D.F.A. testing requires a fluorescent microscope, an instrument not always available in settings with less public health infrastructure.
a202a177aa7226bb	normal	The test can be used on animal tissue that is fresh, frozen, decomposed, or that has been fixed in blocks of paraffin to inactivate the virus.
1e8cbb0db6ab45f4	normal	The D.F.A test can be run only on fresh brain tissue samples that have been kept cold, which can be difficult in areas without reliable electricity.
f44464c52944e2d1	normal	Surprisingly, researchers found that L.N. thirty four was able to detect miniscule amounts of rabies virus genetic material, even in samples so old they had liquefied.
79e5492b399b7c34	normal	Moreover, the condition of the sample did not affect the test's accuracy.
7096f7cc5434d98a	normal	Rabies kills about sixty thousand people annually, mostly in Africa and Asia.
464fcf1137f2f92c	normal	The disease can take months to develop following a person's contact with a rabid animal.
0fb9066ee041b151	normal	Once symptoms appear, rabies is nearly always fatal, so identifying cases and starting treatment early is critical to a patient's survival.
955d6cd1c25143cf	normal	Having a quick, easy-to-run and accurate test to tell if an animal that bit someone is rabid could help doctors decide whether someone needs preventive treatment.
63d3d2f6204c97bc	normal	It could also offer advantages for testing in the United States.
e183ba8e73d09602	normal	Currently, if rabies tests are inconclusive, the bitten person usually is given rabies vaccine as part of post-exposure prophylaxis, at an individual cost often over three thousand dollars.
41d27313c79e2218	normal	The test could decrease the number of inconclusive and false positive tests, thus eliminating unnecessary vaccine use.
c7b10b5f8933f72c	normal	Experts estimate that rabies testing, prevention, and control cost two hundred forty five million dollars annually in the United States.
8aca53eccde6fa7c	normal	About forty to fifty thousand people get rabies P.E.P. in the United States annually.

42d2580757079a15	normal	Tiny Satellite's First Global Map of Ice Clouds
37d79b3038f55f7f	normal	Looking at Earth from the International Space Station, astronauts see big, white clouds spreading across the planet.
4f57dd1a9ba42bab	normal	They cannot distinguish a gray rain cloud from a puffy white cloud.
e31817fa76454413	normal	While satellites can see through many clouds and estimate the liquid precipitation they hold, they can't see the smaller ice particles that create enormous rain clouds.
08f2b560a76604ee	normal	Although it was only designed to last three months, the tiny CubeSat known as IceCube has been orbiting Earth for a full year, collecting data on a hard-to-study type of cloud.
bcfb377b63328774	normal	In that time, it has created a global map of these ice clouds around the planet, which could someday help improve models and forecasts.
9e307e3904aa6fb7	normal	This video can be downloaded at the Scientific Visualization Studio.
b2c3b4ca347106ba	normal	An experimental small satellite has filled this void and captured the first global picture of the small frozen particles inside clouds, normally called ice clouds.
8f7843faa0b5e728	normal	Deployed from the space station in May twenty seventeen, it is testing instruments for their ability to make space-based measurements of the small, frozen crystals that make up ice clouds.
df666cd7a12cca0c	normal	Heavy downpours originate from ice clouds, said Dong Wu, principal investigator at NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center in Greenbelt, Maryland.
925efc3efab9f698	normal	Ice clouds start as tiny particles high in the atmosphere.
cb5476e12e8e6392	normal	Absorbing moisture, the ice crystals grow and become heavier, causing them to fall to lower altitudes.
50f7a146392e22d8	normal	Eventually, the particles get so heavy, they fall and melt to form rain drops.
db7ff149eb5c32a3	normal	The ice crystals may also just stay in the air.
3e054846c4eef60c	normal	Like other clouds, ice clouds affect Earth's energy budget by either reflecting or absorbing the Sun's energy and by affecting the emission of heat from Earth into space.
af89322d6f18f5d2	normal	Thus, ice clouds are key variables in weather and climate models.
6f968660b0462b94	normal	It has created a global map of these ice clouds around the planet, which could someday help improve models and forecasts.
fd871bcb0743d834	normal	This is a three-month average of ice clouds.
5dda726951c509b5	normal	The brightest peak areas represent the largest concentration of ice clouds.
66e0ffa3b1cd7894	normal	They are also the spots with heavy precipitation beneath.
c927bf398ad9b468	normal	They reach up to the top of the troposphere from deep convection, which is normally strongest in the tropics.
b69f3d60607a7b76	normal	Measuring atmospheric ice on a global scale remains highly uncertain because satellites have been unable to detect the amount of small ice particles inside the clouds.
d640582a73637634	normal	These particles are too opaque for infrared and visible sensors to penetrate.
2a9ec2cd55347c28	normal	To overcome that limitation, IceCube was outfitted with a submillimeter radiometer that bridges the missing sensitivity between infrared and microwave wavelengths.
6afd793ae12c1f53	normal	Despite weighing only ten pounds and being about size of a loaf of bread, it is a bona fide spacecraft, complete with three-axis attitude control, deployable solar arrays and a deployable U.H.F. communications antenna.
f2d803a53f8a2a7d	normal	The CubeSat spins around its axis, like a plate spinning on a pole.
8d04569315668870	normal	It points at Earth to take a measurement then looks at the cold space to calibrate.
dbf3ada3601d8633	normal	Originally a thirty-day technology-demonstration mission, it is still fully operational in low-Earth orbit almost a year later.
8be4c0f6e86554ee	normal	It is measuring ice clouds and providing data that's good enough to do some real science, Wu said.
9360fe2c2ce2f058	normal	The hard part about developing the CubeSat is making the commercial parts durable in space, said Tom Johnson, Goddard's Small Satellite manager.
310a9cd005055e87	normal	We bought commercial components and spent a lot of time testing the components making sure each part worked.
b932d3b5cb965638	normal	Over the past year, engineers tested the satellite's limits while on orbit.
521a40bbbdae7e1a	normal	They wanted to see if the instrument's batteries stored enough power to run twenty four hours.
12cd4925129be634	normal	It charges its batteries when the Sun shines on its solar arrays.
14b10805b78d74fd	normal	During the test, safeguards prevented the satellite from losing all its power and ending the mission; however, the test was successful.
693c5600fc447545	normal	The batteries operated all night and recharged during the day.
779859aa6236bbf6	normal	This change made the CubeSat more valuable for science data collection.
a303d68631185cff	normal	While the team planned for the mission to operate for thirty days in space, It does not cost very much to keep it going, Johnson said,
db6944d092e948eb	normal	So we extended the mission due to the outstanding science that it is performing.
65728ff673ec062d	normal	We download data eight to ten times a week. Even if we miss a week, the CubeSat can hold a couple of weeks of data.
8c38e0d4f70e4d87	normal	Johnson says he is not surprised by how long it has lasted.
a7cbb123ea8513e1	normal	It will last about a year, when it will reenter Earth's atmosphere and burn up in.
1b220e0d8711b23b	normal	The team built the spacecraft using funding from the Earth Science Technology Office's In-Space Validation of Earth Science Technologies program.
9f395f0a3752fda8	normal	Small satellites, including CubeSats, are playing an increasingly larger role in exploration, technology demonstration, scientific research and educational investigations at NASA.
59fe8a9ac6d33786	normal	They have been used in planetary space exploration, fundamental Earth and space science.
ce0bf5931cc94bb7	normal	They are used in developing precursor science instruments like cutting-edge laser communications, satellite-to-satellite communications and autonomous movement capabilities.
783be12fc0d7209a	normal	If you answer the phone and hear a recorded message instead of a live person, it's a robocall.
8850f706e94eb7fd	normal	We've seen a significant increase in the number of illegal robocalls because internet-powered phone systems have made it cheap and easy for scammers to make illegal calls from anywhere in the world.
a2d32f2699f0c6d2	normal	They can also hide from law enforcement by displaying fake caller I.D. information.
7b01d7e64e4ce0cd	normal	To date, the F.T.C. has brought more than a hundred lawsuits against over six hundred companies and individuals responsible for billions of illegal robocalls and other Do Not Call violations.
fc360ad1e75d33ba	normal	The F.T.C. also is leading several initiatives to develop technology-based solutions.
18464d84eeadac92	normal	Those initiatives include a series of robocall contests that challenge tech gurus to design tools that block robocalls and help investigators track down and stop robocallers.
d52cd4ae7e6d275f	normal	We're also encouraging industry efforts to combat caller ID spoofing.
e12f4aa63c893225	normal	Here's the F.T.C.'s game plan to combat robocalls:
99db0e56e8847ce5	normal	Continue aggressive law enforcement.
25713443901387cb	normal	Build better tools for investigating robocalls.
d6270c47645c4d56	normal	Coordinate with law enforcement, industry, and other stakeholders.
1e96728279f23ae4	normal	Stimulate and pursue technological solutions.
d595ab2696154076	normal	Congratulations to the prize winners!
4a07da8c35c9ec15	normal	We hope they bring their solutions to the marketplace soon.
5e79849d93856541	normal	Staff would like to thank its contest partners Pindrop Security and the C.R.T.C. for all their help in making this contest a success.
31b8c9ed351ee1bb	normal	Many thanks also to the community for welcoming us back in twenty fifteen!

c561cfac4bf4069d	normal	The plan must explain how it will comply with the Surgeon General health warning display requirements.
3265a0e8095bcd84	normal	Below, organized chronologically, are links to approved plans and the letters approving them.
0d34a941966c3f9c	normal	Ten Things You Can Do to Avoid Fraud
76ed0f1a773ae88e	normal	Crooks use clever schemes to defraud millions of people every year.
fb70761f74b8e791	normal	They often combine new technology with old tricks to get people to send money or give out personal information.
7d702206b55487d9	normal	Here are some practical tips to help you stay a step ahead.
33bb516468c98e3b	normal	Spot imposters.
720c5b6edc5e42d8	normal	Scammers often pretend to be someone you trust, like a government official, a family member, a charity, or a company you do business with.
feb3eba6a6e91abb	normal	Don't send money or give out personal information in response to an unexpected request - whether it comes as a text, a phone call, or an email.
d7d9e25e8e845bb4	normal	Do online searches.
0b1a490a29f9259d	normal	Type a company or product name into your favorite search engine with words like "review," "complaint" or "scam."
e493f0a8e11a5d71	normal	Or search for a phrase that describes your situation, like I.R.S. call.
281f1732c07351c1	normal	You can even search for phone numbers to see if other people have reported them as scams.
b27205ffe168b931	normal	Don't believe your caller ID.
2803ba631fdf4f19	normal	Technology makes it easy for scammers to fake caller I.D. information, so the name and number you see aren't always real.
300d6f84a8accee6	normal	If someone calls asking for money or personal information, hang up.
b5de7bc3b9363d87	normal	If you think the caller might be telling the truth, call back to a number you know is genuine.
3915e899d0d633cd	normal	Don't pay upfront for a promise.
5f444552096346bf	normal	Someone might ask you to pay in advance for things like debt relief, credit and loan offers, mortgage assistance, or a job.
8377d1d2a917f65d	normal	They might even say you've won a prize, but first you have to pay taxes or fees.
1aae3e8e0aeb215e	normal	If you do, they will probably take the money and disappear.
69cf7a92472103c7	normal	Consider how you pay.
f3d37e098aa2eb30	normal	Credit cards have significant fraud protection built in, but some payment methods don't.
1130346bfe2ecf18	normal	Wiring money through services like Western Union or MoneyGram is risky because it's nearly impossible to get your money back.
3cc98b89371bb138	normal	That's also true for reloadable cards like MoneyPak, Reloadit or Vanilla.
7ee9aca1a715573d	normal	Government offices and honest companies won't require you to use these payment methods.
77a26f6d6d60dc67	normal	Talk to someone.
77d85d5a5eb67817	normal	Before you give up your money or personal information, talk to someone you trust.
f195bec8af4b29e5	normal	Con artists want you to make decisions in a hurry.
2984047edb5a6503	normal	They might even threaten you.
116cfbba300787aa	normal	Slow down, check out the story, do an online search, consult an expert, or just tell a friend.
8d369437763b9b99	normal	Hang up on robocalls.
77a4810b5e6f5022	normal	If you answer the phone and hear a recorded sales pitch, hang up and report it.
43aa2121e05cbb45	normal	These calls are illegal, and often the products are bogus.
86e6b9e66ad2cebb	normal	Don't press one to speak to a person or to be taken off the list.
54737d821cb19364	normal	That could lead to more calls.
12df803c5dcb4cf6	normal	Be skeptical about free trial offers.
2e988a4103075e1d	normal	Some companies use free trials to sign you up for products and bill you every month until you cancel.
55370bad49e6090f	normal	Before you agree to a free trial, research the company and read the cancellation policy.
85dabc30829236e3	normal	And always review your monthly statements for charges you don't recognize.
7fe5596fa421c104	normal	Don't deposit a check and wire money back.
fb94d597b5eb2b3c	normal	By law, banks must make funds from deposited checks available within days, but uncovering a fake check can take weeks.
1f90c99c72bfef5f	normal	If a check you deposit turns out to be a fake, you're responsible for repaying the bank.
dd569d3c8645dba1	normal	Promoters of alternative investment and money-making opportunities sometimes make their deals seem like a sure thing.
57cbde3e965b59fc	normal	The truth is that the higher the potential reward, the higher the risk.
17504559ee1dde78	normal	Don't do business with someone who tries to convince you otherwise.
82b78c12f5dc571d	normal	Dishonest promoters often are vague about the nature of the investment and focus instead on the money you'll make.
3ca54e25c96f82d1	normal	To close the deal, they cite phony statistics, exaggerate the significance of a current event, claim they will guarantee the investment, or stress how unique their offer is.
6ecc3737146f550d	normal	And they almost always try to rush you into a decision.
a548823924f3e640	normal	Investment decisions demand your time and careful consideration.
71659e9e5d2bebb4	normal	Take your time.
fb78b68e7f45362b	normal	Using sales scripts, scam artists may create the impression that only a few shares or partnership units are left in a "sure-fire" investment.
f213ad944570c9b1	normal	They try to convince you that you'll miss out on a big opportunity if you don't send them thousands of dollars by overnight courier or money transfer.
c72a6bba4c3ae498	normal	But if you do, you will lose your money.
e959e48c632f1c1d	normal	They insist on money transfers because it is nearly impossible to trace the money or get it back.
3a9c88c4f81c4567	normal	Do some research.
17af1b1e64c3a41e	normal	It's best to get an independent appraisal of the specific asset, business, or investment you're considering.
ee4ff58d0611c539	normal	An appraisal offered by the promoters could be fake.
be77556c430f8207	normal	Talk to the previous owners of an asset or business for its history.
b97e33f40c89349b	normal	Be aware that some dishonest promoters hire "shills," people who lie about their success with an investment to convince you to buy it.
b4e88f3a3e5cda9f	normal	Discuss all investment ideas or plans with an accountant, an attorney, or another advisor you know and trust.
43772940015b683c	normal	Be skeptical.
a6959ad3b5a09834	normal	Scam artists lie. Their success depends on having an airtight answer for everything.
fbcdde08313d9d51	normal	Don't let appearances fool you.
fa5813ef0e1616c9	normal	For a few dollars, anyone can incorporate an entity.
9585d988119723a0	normal	Scammers can produce slick promotional materials, or buy a toll-free number.
acff8ad0d95692ab	normal	Sales representatives should tell you the risk of particular investments.
3d1ae8262c325de8	normal	Honest risk disclosures may say you could lose your whole investment.
10a65f63e4dba906	normal	Be particularly suspicious of sales pitches that play down risk or portray written risk disclosures as routine formalities required by the government.
6b5293df6aed476b	normal	Later, when you try to recover the money you lost, dishonest promoters could use those same risk disclosures against you.
739a77c3484ee520	normal	Find out who you're dealing with.
89333e37198aebcd	normal	Can you find published information about the company in which you're investing, or someone you trust who has heard of the company?
694c1c5ccf1a1f85	normal	Do an internet search with the name of the company and words like review, scam, or complaint.
5c591deeeb336733	normal	Look through several pages of search results.
50cab7fb1cd1e644	normal	It's wise to check with law enforcement agencies in the community where the promoters are located.
da10bd19dce596f0	normal	Keep in mind that it may be too soon for the company's victims to realize they've been defrauded or to have filed complaints.
16bfc3fe2b360b2c	normal	Dishonest promoters often operate a particular scam for a short time and close down before they can be detected.
fa2b211733ca90a2	normal	Often, they reopen under another name, selling another investment scam.
559031288592d0a2	normal	In addition, they may lie about their name or their business history, or even pay people to be "references."
13b108eba35a518c	normal	Ask if the investment has a track record.
e30f38c3843e4d37	normal	Scam artists often use news stories about the success of legitimate companies as bait by claiming that their "opportunity" is similar to that of a "hot" money-maker.
b9cca8ba95bc06b0	normal	Unfortunately, success stories of other companies in the field are irrelevant for your purposes.
7daafa37e3dca67e	normal	Get the track record of the company you're considering investing in and the background of the people promoting it.
9c1ec5d890d4bec1	normal	Get details.
86c9da484e3b528f	normal	Legitimate companies account for investors' money at all times.
58f784d2f33a4c33	normal	Ask for written proof of how much of your money is going to the actual investment and how much is going to commissions, promoters' profits, and marketing costs.
222e2f1894cd2abb	normal	If most of your money is slated to cover expenses and costs, much less will be available to earn a return.
41a30e3430015a4f	normal	Suspect A Health Care Scam? Here's What to Do.
54e3fd93ec853489	normal	If you see a headline one day, you can be sure a related scam will follow soon after.
d50f841c1c8ba907	normal	With the Affordable Care Act in the news, scammers are on the prowl, calling, emailing, sending letters and texts, trying to get your money - and your personal and financial information.
7c3c863208bb0a0d	normal	Scammers know you have questions about the new Health Insurance Marketplace, and they're taking advantage of that to mislead you.
5b96b0331a2d32ad	normal	Some people have contacted the Federal Trade Commission, the nation's consumer protection agency, about health care scams they've seen so far.
c12dcae6356c21ab	normal	Here's what those scams look like - and what you can do about them.
04e57dffd7726ff4	normal	Charging you for help getting new insurance.
e2a85eeb1dffd422	normal	Someone contacts you, offering to help you navigate the Health Insurance Marketplace for a fee - or saying that you need a new insurance card now or you'll have to pay a penalty.
992a177a1a737312	normal	Regardless of the set up, their goal is to get your bank account or credit card number.
c5f3a0646e644bd3	normal	Don't give your information.
ffbc19f38fdfec56	normal	The people who offer legitimate help with the Health Insurance Marketplace - sometimes called Navigators or Assisters - are not allowed to charge you.
b308713fd2786236	normal	In fact, you can't pay them.
c9a91223e81c836a	normal	What's more, you don't need to buy a special insurance card, or pay any penalties for not buying one, either.
4fd05589b04ad8dd	normal	Bottom line: Never give your money or your information to anyone who contacts you.
784cbd95ef66b753	normal	Medicare cards.
2b76266b811d6971	normal	Someone gets in touch, saying you need a new Medicare card because of Obamacare.
4ac4a947ab651ea8	normal	They tell you that you'll lose Medicare coverage if you don't pay a fee for a new card or give them your Social Security number and bank account or credit card number.
f90776b834cc08fe	normal	The Affordable Care Act doesn't say you need a new Medicare card, or another health insurance card.
d5d1b5bbdf94e024	normal	Nor does the law say you'll lose Medicare coverage.
236906b171ff5d76	normal	Don't give your personal or financial information to anyone who contacts you.
79e9ca4c76048fa4	normal	When in doubt, call one eight hundred Medicare, before you give anyone your money or information.
9db005086210124e	normal	Medical discount scams.
bf277ff2fd013116	normal	Someone contacts you, offering discounts on health services and products.
b33acab36a4dc8f1	normal	They might say the discount plan will save you money and that it meets the minimum coverage required under "Obamacare" so you won't have to pay a penalty or look at other plans.
b3a35733be063ad9	normal	Medical discount plans are not health insurance.
11ea8bedd64006b4	normal	Sometimes, medical discount plans illegally pretend to be insurance.
1d372793fc180b2a	normal	Ask specific questions and don't pay until you read the terms.
ac442cb5fd83e1e7	normal	Your state insurance commissioner's office can tell you if a health plan is insurance.
0acbbf3876691ec5	normal	Most medical discount plans are a membership in a "club" that claims to offer reduced prices from certain doctors, certain pharmacies, and on some procedures.
73897aa050ee2532	normal	Some medical discount plans provide legitimate discounts, but others are scams that don't deliver on the medical services promised.
509c1cd7823bc115	normal	Others are attempts to get your personal or financial information, so the scammer can use it to commit identity fraud.
150914a45cebe9da	normal	Someone claiming to be an insurance agent gets in touch to say you should "act now" to get your new insurance.
2d8a28748a2adf52	normal	They may promise to get you a special deal or help you avoid a penalty.
d94b494417f3f11f	normal	Or they might say they can help you avoid losing access to your current doctors under Medicare, unless you sign up for a Medicare Advantage Plan.
437ec49e95bd83db	normal	If you have Medicare, the open enrollment for Medicare Part D and Medicare Advantage Plans stays the same: October fifteenth to December seventh, two thousand thirteen.
4815bc8353ff1675	normal	You don't have to do anything different because of the Affordable Care Act.
6f97cf927b8fb8d2	normal	While some insurance agents can help you with your application through the Health Insurance Marketplace, don't give your personal information or pay any money to someone who contacts you.
0d6c3ebdff2ef963	normal	I can help you. Really.
d817a4afbdd46108	normal	Someone contacts you, offering to help you navigate the Health Insurance Marketplace.
8128e6b887947693	normal	There really are trained people who can help. But experts expect scammers to wade in here, too.
f175510591474d95	normal	See what they do.
07d7015b1286ac50	normal	The helpers might be called navigators, assistors, counselors, connectors, or something similar.
e991d7a6c1309847	normal	The important thing is what they do.
499ca5b4098fd253	normal	The official helpers will try to help you find the plan that serves you best.
9cd059b5d5c11baf	normal	If you want, they might help you get signed up through HealthCare dot gov.
7d8acc25f3274ccf	normal	They will not try to sell you a particular plan or ask for money to help you.
f5917acdaf7a3365	normal	If someone does that, chances are they're not an official trained helper.
35fb0b224a026047	normal	I'm from the government.
ce565681363dc93b	normal	No. They're not. The government will not call you about your health insurance; and no one from the government will ask you to verify your Social Security number or bank information.
844131aad5f61ac7	normal	Some government agencies might send you a letter (for example, Medicare and the I.R.S.), but they will never ask you to wire them money or give your credit card number.
f99ea7d023a172a9	normal	If someone calls, emails, or texts and says they're from the government, it's a scam.
9a8e529104bd203d	normal	Report any scams you see.
c7ac063f7fb29c83	normal	Your reports give us the information we need to launch investigations, and put scammers out of business.
ba2d671eadb0f338	normal	If you're shopping in the Health Insurance Marketplace, do it at healthcare dot gov.
6761ccb97f673853	normal	People who try to sign you up elsewhere just might be scamming you.
956e15b696e71423	normal	The electric car has a long and storied history.
20391d4b660a5f58	normal	Travel back in time as we explore the history of the electric car.
36400694faa1db95	normal	Introduced more than one hundred years ago, electric cars are seeing a rise in popularity today for many of the same reasons they were first popular.
5a86d57899b3d01f	normal	Whether it's a hybrid, plug-in hybrid or all-electric, the demand for electric drive vehicles will continue to climb as prices drop and consumers look for ways to save money at the pump.
69b4966d62325154	normal	Currently more than three percent of new vehicle sales, electric vehicles sales could to grow to nearly seven percent - or six point six million per year - worldwide by twenty twenty.
00f36be5e407ac5c	normal	With this growing interest in electric vehicles, we are taking a look at where this technology has been and where it's going.
a8c1fd9247373ceb	normal	Travel back in time with us as we explore the history of the electric car.
542a70193cc9d3d4	normal	The Birth Of The Electric Vehicle.
3de1d3d0aa227e54	normal	It's hard to pinpoint the invention of the electric car to one inventor or country.
adbe2d4f67f2292d	normal	Instead it was a series of breakthroughs - from the battery to the electric motor - in the eighteen hundreds that led to the first electric vehicle on the road.
7e24172477960f62	normal	In the early part of the century, innovators in Hungary, the Netherlands and the United States - including a blacksmith from Vermont - began toying with the concept of a battery-powered vehicle.
0cc2864a595dc2ea	normal	They created some of the first small-scale electric cars.
da857faecc8e1339	normal	And while Robert Anderson, a British inventor, developed the first crude electric carriage around this same time, it wasn't until the second half of the nineteenth century that French and English inventors built the first practical electric cars.
eae63093b7c3d8e8	normal	Here in the U.S., the first successful electric car made its debut around eighteen ninety thanks to William Morrison, a chemist who lived in Des Moines, Iowa.
73ca4d648838f25e	normal	His six-passenger vehicle capable of a top speed of fourteen miles per hour was little more than an electrified wagon, but it helped spark interest in electric vehicles.
b07b09e253522d83	normal	Over the next few years, electric vehicles from different automakers began popping up across the U.S.
60748d7b8d350a56	normal	New York City even had a fleet of more than sixty electric taxis.
f94c175563985837	normal	By nineteen hundred, electric cars were at their heyday, accounting for around a third of all vehicles on the road.
5a1beb23c11b6bd4	normal	During the next ten years, they continued to show strong sales.
371314d58ce11721	normal	The Early Rise And Fall Of The Electric Car.
14e96f9a100c286b	normal	To understand the popularity of electric vehicles circa nineteen hundred, it is also important to understand the development of the personal vehicle and the other options available.
1383585baa0f799b	normal	At the turn of the twentieth century, the horse was still the primary mode of transportation.
7056095b1cde2615	normal	But as Americans became more prosperous, they turned to the newly invented motor vehicle - available in steam, gasoline or electric versions - to get around.
7d455c162bfa70d4	normal	Steam was a tried and true energy source, having proved reliable for powering factories and trains.
9832f4eb6384f004	normal	Some of the first self-propelled vehicles in the late seventeen hundreds relied on steam.
355dfc584bea0bdf	normal	Yet it took until the eighteen seventys for the technology to take hold in cars.
d173ac89b0c6bee0	normal	Part of this is because steam wasn't very practical for personal vehicles.
882043736737ae29	normal	Steam vehicles required long startup times - sometimes up to forty five minutes in the cold - and would need to be refilled with water, limiting their range.
b3643e54c9272126	normal	As electric vehicles came onto the market, so did a new type of vehicle - the gasoline-powered car - thanks to improvements to the internal combustion engine in the eighteen hundreds.
dafb0a106bec9294	normal	While gasoline cars had promise, they weren't without their faults.
60fc36508951d8db	normal	They required a lot of manual effort to drive - changing gears was no easy task.
7439b7997827e684	normal	They needed to be started with a hand crank, making them difficult for some to operate.
d46f6c69fe3fbe3e	normal	They were also noisy, and their exhaust was unpleasant.
c65557e8b5b700b0	normal	Electric cars didn't have any of the issues associated with steam or gasoline.
2fafe0f917b95d41	normal	They were quiet, easy to drive and didn't emit a smelly pollutant like the other cars of the time.
1ef39c21374c1a8b	normal	Electric cars quickly became popular with urban residents - especially women.
21f49aee025cc79a	normal	They were perfect for short trips around the city, and poor road conditions outside cities meant few cars of any type could venture farther.
2eb377b742e0aa82	normal	As more people gained access to electricity in the nineteen tens, it became easier to charge electric cars, adding to their popularity with all walks of life.
e3a4bb25d55f016a	normal	Many innovators at the time took note of the electric vehicle's high demand, exploring ways to improve the technology.
ebe0a5c3abb238ca	normal	For example, Ferdinand Porsche, founder of the sports car company by the same name, developed an electric car in eighteen ninety eight.
16f36c1391aa9708	normal	Around the same time, he created the world's first hybrid electric car - a vehicle that is powered by electricity and a gas engine.
2b9c46cefc9f0a65	normal	Thomas Edison, one of the world's most prolific inventors, thought electric vehicles were the superior technology and worked to build a better electric vehicle battery.
779dbdaae5378b4c	normal	Even Henry Ford, who was friends with Edison, partnered with Edison to explore options for a low-cost electric car in nineteen fourteen, according to Wired.
c1508638ae23f9c9	normal	Yet, it was Henry Ford's mass-produced Model T that dealt a blow to the electric car.
06883a78a7d30dbb	normal	Introduced in nineteen oh eight, the Model T made gasoline-powered cars widely available and affordable.
6158515d286d0771	normal	By nineteen twelve, the gasoline car cost only six hundred fifty dollars, while an electric roadster sold for seventeen hundred fifty dollars.
548b34d154ce0dbc	normal	That same year, Charles Kettering introduced the electric starter, eliminating the need for the hand crank and giving rise to more gasoline-powered vehicle sales.
b5af6cf8947075bc	normal	Other developments also contributed to the decline of the electric vehicle.
83fe674c1332a477	normal	By the nineteen twentys, the U.S. had a better system of roads connecting cities, and Americans wanted to get out and explore.
9b75675bf79abe37	normal	With the discovery of Texas crude oil, gas became cheap and readily available for rural Americans, and filling stations began popping up across the country.
dacc8e197a4c50be	normal	In comparison, very few Americans outside of cities had electricity at that time.
da8fe5e993f8ba2d	normal	In the end, electric vehicles all but disappeared by nineteen thirty five.
1cc5af1ed2e457f2	normal	Gas Shortages Spark Interest In Electric Vehicles.
3628f0e69537e4af	normal	Over the next thirty years or so, electric vehicles entered a sort of dark ages with little advancement in the technology.
b7a505fcb5413bb7	normal	Cheap, abundant gasoline and continued improvement in the internal combustion engine hampered demand for alternative fuel vehicles.
79b93e37cbb95279	normal	Fast forward to the late nineteen sixtys and early nineteen seventys.
30e4b54f1cf5fe54	normal	Soaring oil prices and gasoline shortages - peaking with the nineteen seventy three Arab Oil Embargo - created a growing interest in lowering the U.S.'s dependence on foreign oil.
9391c62c7fbfbcdc	normal	Congress took note and passed the Electric and Hybrid Vehicle Research, Development, and Demonstration Act of nineteen seventy six.
f62425fee6d9da34	normal	It authorized the Energy Department to support research and development in electric and hybrid vehicles.
fd479f7bce2e3c36	normal	Around this same time, many big and small automakers began exploring options for alternative fuel vehicles, including electric cars.
bb0e06fc730ea93b	normal	For example, General Motors developed a prototype for an urban electric car that it displayed at the Environmental Protection Agency's First Symposium on Low Pollution Power Systems Development.
00f4fa715bb7b044	normal	The American Motor Company produced electric delivery jeeps that the United States Postal Service used in a nineteen seventy five test program.
bfb423f90ed7389b	normal	Even NASA helped raise the profile of the electric vehicle when its electric Lunar rover became the first manned vehicle to drive on the moon in nineteen seventy one.
e59d5726448dd08e	normal	Yet, the vehicles developed and produced in the nineteen seventys still suffered from drawbacks compared to gasoline-powered cars.
c41d54400eb8232c	normal	Electric vehicles during this time had limited performance - usually topping at speeds of forty five miles per hour - and their typical range was limited to forty miles before needing to be recharged.
bb727616a9b1c102	normal	Environmental Concern Drives Electric Vehicles Forward.
81cb051fe5155d5d	normal	Fast forward again - this time to the nineteen ninetys.
f21064866556be45	normal	In the twenty years since the long gas lines of the nineteen seventys, interest in electric vehicles had mostly died down.
c910e19fbc4beea9	normal	But new federal and state regulations begin to change things.
c10a2cb9ea0a0704	normal	The passage of the nineteen ninety Clean Air Act Amendment and the nineteen ninety two Energy Policy Act helped create a renewed interest in electric vehicles in the U.S.
b0cd475a791b8729	normal	During this time, automakers began modifying some of their popular vehicle models into electric vehicles.
0d9491cbc54749e8	normal	This meant that electric vehicles now achieved speeds and performance much closer to gasoline-powered vehicles, and many of them had a range of sixty miles.
d9414c75455a3d91	normal	One of the most well-known electric cars during this time was G.M.'s E.V. one, a car that was heavily featured in the two thousand six documentary Who Killed the Electric Car?
5bd19e273171abba	normal	Instead of modifying an existing vehicle, G.M. designed and developed the E.V. one from the ground up.
7f5eee25c7882627	normal	With a range of eighty miles and the ability to accelerate from zero to fifty miles per hour in just seven seconds, it quickly gained a cult following.
e0b7c8e9142e0e44	normal	But because of high production costs, it was never commercially viable, and G.M. discontinued it in two thousand one.
5e0b1ba898247310	normal	With a booming economy, a growing middle class and low gas prices in the late nineteen ninetys, many consumers didn't worry about fuel-efficient vehicles.
f8cc20b482b55c32	normal	Even though there wasn't much public attention to electric vehicles at this time, behind the scenes, scientists and engineers were working to improve electric vehicle technology, including batteries.
4e1d685211f7d2bb	normal	A New Beginning For Electric Cars
8f3faf7d2ae7d85c	normal	The true revival of the electric vehicle didn't happen until around the start of the twenty first century.
03d83b88f8836017	normal	Depending on whom you ask, it was one of two events that sparked the interest we see today in electric vehicles.
57c8dfb7456201bb	normal	The first turning point many have suggested was the introduction of the Toyota Prius.
ca11ee855968d04f	normal	Released in Japan in nineteen ninety seven, the Prius became the world's first mass-produced hybrid electric vehicle.
e25bb8d71fcd45a2	normal	In two thousand, the Prius was released worldwide, and it became an instant success with celebrities, helping to raise the profile of the car.
d72c421b2b2988b4	normal	To make the Prius a reality, Toyota used a nickel metal hydride battery - a technology that was supported by the Energy Department's research.
2b7e3caf6cd7ce1b	normal	Since then, rising gasoline prices and growing concern about carbon pollution have helped make the Prius the best-selling hybrid worldwide during the past decade.
2ea1013ce5ca746a	normal	Historical footnote: Before the Prius could be introduced in the U.S., Honda released the Insight hybrid in nineteen ninety nine, making it the first hybrid sold in the U.S. since the early nineteen hundreds.
46d667cb18338617	normal	The other event that helped reshape electric vehicles was the announcement in two thousand six that a small Silicon Valley startup, Tesla Motors, would start producing a luxury electric sports car.
04af1f2861eab497	normal	In twenty ten, Tesla received a four hundred sixty five million dollar loan from the Department of Energy's Loan Programs Office.
70a5e8197b8e5e3f	normal	In the short time since then, Tesla has won wide acclaim for its cars and has become the largest auto industry employer in California.
d7dcec23c3d99906	normal	Tesla's announcement and subsequent success spurred many big automakers to accelerate work on their own electric vehicles.
deb85c1dfa8124ca	normal	In late twenty ten, the Chevy Volt and the Nissan Leaf were released in the U.S. market.
cfdcbed1bac72e0f	normal	The first commercially available plug-in hybrid, the Volt has a gasoline engine that supplements its electric drive once the battery is depleted, allowing consumers to drive on electric for most trips.
06a7581111c14cb4	normal	In comparison, the Leaf is an all-electric vehicle (often called a battery-electric vehicle, an electric vehicle or just an E.V. for short), meaning it is only powered by an electric motor.
9db734519914e01f	normal	Over the next few years, other automakers began rolling out electric vehicles in the U.S.
6c87ced59edfb2f5	normal	Yet, consumers were still faced with one of the early problems of the electric vehicle - where to charge their vehicles on the go.
3374f37e9935c5c0	normal	Through the Recovery Act, the Energy Department invested more than one hundred fifteen million dollars to help build a nation-wide charging infrastructure.
91f18dd8d16eba09	normal	It installed more than eighteen thousand residential, commercial and public chargers across the country.
2fb51e696077079e	normal	Automakers and other private businesses also installed their own chargers at key locations in the U.S., bringing today's total of public electric vehicle chargers to more than eight thousand different locations.
907172c50d061091	normal	At the same time, new battery technology began hitting the market, helping to improve a plug-in electric vehicle's range.
47febbc7b97b7176	normal	In addition to the battery technology in nearly all of the first generation hybrids, the Department's research also helped develop the lithium-ion battery technology used in the Volt.
69d850cb181ad2cd	normal	More recently, the Department's investment in battery research and development has helped cut electric vehicle battery costs by fifty percent in the last four years.
8923855e8d4009ca	normal	This in turn has helped lower the costs of electric vehicles, making them more affordable for consumers.
a9bf803f2aa62808	normal	Consumers now have more choices than ever when it comes to buying an electric vehicle.
3821de3d3b2caacd	normal	Today, there are twenty three plug-in electric and thirty six hybrid models available in a variety of sizes - from the two-passenger Smart E.D. to the midsized Ford C-Max Energi to the B.M.W. I three S.U.V.
9d485feb2a46d0a9	normal	As gasoline prices continue to rise and the prices on electric vehicles continue to drop, electric vehicles are gaining in popularity.
a56f9642361b2253	normal	There are more than two hundred thirty four thousand plug-in electric vehicles and three point three million hybrids on the road in the U.S. today.
8113f5c193208193	normal	It's hard to tell where the future will take electric vehicles, but it's clear they hold a lot of potential for creating a more sustainable future.
f8170279d41042e5	normal	If we transitioned all the light-duty vehicles in the U.S. to hybrids or plug-in electric vehicles using our current technology mix, we could reduce our dependence on foreign oil by thirty-sixty percent.
3176ce8345071b19	normal	It would lower the carbon pollution from the transportation sector by as much as twenty percent.
56c0c5772fa44b7d	normal	To help reach these emissions savings, in twenty twelve President Obama launched the E.V. Everywhere Grand Challenge.
ac9d849b854659bc	normal	This is an Energy Department initiative that brings together America's best and brightest scientists, engineers and businesses to make plug-in electric vehicles as affordable as today's gasoline-powered vehicles.
8e2edbe9c73a9ec0	normal	On the battery front, the Department's Joint Center for Energy Storage Research at Argonne National Laboratory is working to overcome the biggest scientific and technical barriers that prevent large-scale improvements of batteries.
25b688ec6fb665de	normal	And the Department's Advanced Research Projects Agency is advancing game-changing technologies that could alter how we think of electric vehicles.
df6bd445fe00252c	normal	In the end, only time will tell what road electric vehicles will take in the future.
c151f4661175a0f8	normal	Since two thousand, U.S. homes have ballooned in size, on average becoming thirty percent larger.
0fc5b3d864a43c2d	normal	Yet despite this fact, newer homes only consume two percent more energy.
c06464e2c5d6b894	normal	While some of this can be attributed to more homes being built in warmer regions like the South, a lot of it is thanks in part to improved energy efficiency.
0772531f1a6026db	normal	From more efficient appliances to better building materials, advances in residential technologies are helping homeowners save energy.
98f0a5c5b9f13c02	normal	Many of these technologies can trace their roots back to the Energy Department.
675a7e13fb1b398c	normal	Through investments at the early stages of technology, tougher appliance standards and collaboration with researchers at our National Labs and private companies to develop energy-saving technologies,
5018af8b86e5fdd2	normal	The Energy Department is helping lay the foundation for more efficient homes.
e67d084cb50c1064	normal	Explore the top four Energy Department inventions that are helping homeowners save energy and money.
74854684e7946986	normal	Tou might even find some of the innovations in your home!
6c8c678e8ba718d5	normal	Four. Loose fill fiberglass insulation.
9c2b3f0041368bc4	normal	Hidden in walls, attics and floors, insulation helps keep homes comfortable with little thought from the homeowner.
183bad076f080099	normal	In nineteen ninety two, private insulation manufacturer Energy Savings Solutions, Inc., reached out to Oak Ridge National Laboratory to find ways to improve loose-fill fiberglass insulation.
4f8fec9f779edcbb	normal	One of the most common types of attic insulation.
f968afa340441b44	normal	After discovering that in cold climates this type of insulation resulted in heat losses of up to fifty percent, Oak Ridge researchers provided the guidance necessary to substantially improve the insulation's performance.
2bc529055d9817f3	normal	Oak Ridge's findings sparked an industry-wide reformulation of loose-fill fiberglass insulation, leading manufacturers to redesign their products for better fiber dispersion.
84411b06a387f8aa	normal	The findings also had an impact on state building codes.
f70f836d3c4e0af2	normal	Minnesota rewrote its energy code to require manufacturers to label insulation based on the coldest expected winter conditions.
3ebfd5dd16a225ae	normal	Today, nearly seventy five percent of homes use this type of improved loose-fill fiberglass insulation, and researchers estimate the changes have helped consumers in cold climates save ten percent on heating costs.
225942f1628075bc	normal	Looking to the future of building envelope technologies, the Energy Department is working to develop new more efficient insulation that can be added to existing homes and buildings.
ece0f73d992170a4	normal	One such project with Industrial Science and Technology Network focuses on using nanotechnology to develop cost-effective, environmentally friendly foam insulation that is more efficient than current technology.
19ef01a5a521adea	normal	If successfully commercialized, the company estimates the technology could save eight billion dollars a year in heating and cooling costs.
a724f809bda6c54e	normal	Three. Electric Head Pump Water Heaters.
bb05101af210ecdf	normal	Since the start of the Energy Department in the late nineteen seventys, the Building Technologies Office has spearheaded research and development in energy-efficient residential water heating solutions
405bafb96aa0d976	normal	In the late nineteen ninetys, the Department began exploring electric heat pump water heaters.
ab57625818248142	normal	This early research - plus the growing demand for more efficient water heaters spurred by the Energy Star program - laid the groundwork for the electric heat pump water heater market.
2dff1ffaa80476f6	normal	In two thousand nine, Oak Ridge National Lab worked with General Electric to bring the GeoSpring water heater, the first Energy Star qualified electric heat pump water heater, to the market.
a6acb1e9158584cd	normal	Part heat pump, part conventional storage water heater, the GeoSpring water heater uses sixty two percent less energy than a standard fifty-gallon electric water heater.
a30995dd332cf1c7	normal	Heat pump water heater sales have skyrocketed from about two thousand units sold in two thousand six to more than thirty four thousand in twenty twelve.
eee9054f599d5fa1	normal	Today, seven manufacturers offer Energy Star qualified electric heat pump water heaters under more than a dozen brand names.
8833e792c0873e68	normal	Based on the national average residential electricity price in twenty twelve, electric heat pump water heaters can save homeowners about three hundred dollars a year on their energy bills.
2dd8d45f6b1f4a5d	normal	Even with this advancement, there is still plenty of room to improve water heaters, which consume more energy than all other household appliances combined.
76b109ea32410c2b	normal	The Energy Department continues to move water heater technology forward, most recently announcing funding for two new projects developed by America's small businesses.
cee054a6c23b0336	normal	Two. Energy Efficient Refrigerator Compressor.
a5a4825c13d0332c	normal	Over the years, refrigerators have changed dramatically - from a box cooled by an ice block to a WiFi-connected smart appliance.
75f6862bb2807784	normal	But even though fridges have gotten bigger on average and have more features, they use about twenty five percent less energy than those built in nineteen seventy five.
b9c25b333f06136f	normal	Between nineteen seventy eight and nineteen eighty, researchers at Oak Ridge National Lab and Columbus Products Company developed a fridge compressor that was nearly fifty percent more efficient than the typical compressor at the time.
e3ffe62f9b16262f	normal	Manufacturers incorporated the new advanced compressor into multiple refrigerator lines throughout the nineteen eightys and nineteen ninetys - helping save consumers six dollars billion in energy costs over that same period.
d237f6ec8f523235	normal	The advanced compressor also allowed the Department to implement more stringent energy standards for fridges in nineteen ninety three and two thousand one.
7343732a9de2de01	normal	Today, more than one hundred million refrigerators in homes across the country use an advanced compressor that can trace its roots to the Department's pioneering research and development in the late nineteen seventys.
b2a09737a73e9e83	normal	Over the past four decades, fridges have improved dramatically, consuming on average only four hundred eighty kilowatt hours of electricity a year.
e9c6d5f19e68af25	normal	As manufacturers continue to look for new ways to cut the fridge's energy use, magnetic refrigeration is one area that holds promise.
e5a98175f0f7c74e	normal	Recently, G.E. announced it is working with Oak Ridge to develop a new type of fridge based on magnetic refrigeration, a technology that uses no refrigerants or compressors and is twenty percent more efficient than today's technology.
24acbf3992171dd3	normal	One. Beyond Double Pane Windows
31b3a98d9a71fcef	normal	While the invention of double-pane windows dates back to nineteen thirty five, a true turning point in the technology came in the eightys with a collaboration between the Energy Department, private industry and Lawrence Berkeley National Lab.
3cee6bff3a0fd681	normal	The first breakthrough was low-emissivity coatings - a technology applied to glazing layers that allows visible light to pass through a window while trapping heat.
40f704c1f85fd4ad	normal	Low E coatings had been around since World War Two in specialty applications like oven windows, but it was initial research and development by Berkeley Lab and a start-up company that led to the commercialization of the technology for use in homes.
c1e6a1440cc0c349	normal	In nineteen eighty one, Suntek introduced the first low E window technology on the market.
a3a03da1aa57d2a6	normal	By nineteen eighty eight, low E windows accounted for twenty percent of window sales.
f552f30bb84838e6	normal	Today, more than eighty percent of residential windows and nearly fifty percent of commercial windows sold every year in the U.S. have low E coatings, saving consumers billions of dollars in energy costs.
a54e8a55e750dffe	normal	Berkeley Lab researchers continued to work with industry partners to develop even more energy-efficient window designs.
4c0a416ba4ac6c15	normal	By replacing the air with an insulating gas between two window panes, researchers were able to further decrease heat loss through windows in cold climates.
88da87d38ef21907	normal	They then added an additional glazing layer with low E coating to create a triple-pane window with two low E coatings and an argon and krypton gas mixture that filled the space between each pane.
2fd14f160ee88df0	normal	These highly insulating window designs can perform as well as - or even better than - a highly insulating wall, helping to dramatically reduce a building's energy loss.
d373d3641ec72798	normal	The future of windows looks bright as the Energy Department continues to invest in research and development to reduce the costs of highly insulating windows and make window replacements cost-effective for consumers.
f1c47aa1c1951c1a	normal	One promising project is the National Renewable Energy Lab's work on insulating window films - a clear layer of insulation that is added to existing windows.
903d3262bb54e192	normal	We estimate that the films could reduce building energy use by as much as thirty three percent, creating a simple payback for window retrofits of less than one year.
82356e16635179f7	normal	For ways to incorporate energy-saving technologies into your home, check out Energy Saver.
8cc63271eaf9736f	normal	What are the key facts?
c3bcd3ae4f3fb7cf	normal	Through investments at the early stages of technology, tougher appliance standards and collaboration with researchers at our National Labs and private companies, the Energy Department is helping lay the foundation for more efficient homes.
6f24b4556a2ce453	normal	Rebecca Matulka is a digital communications specialist for the Energy Department.
0f0ccea736a5386b	normal	She covers all things energy efficiency - from fuel cells and vehicle technologies to advancements in manufacturing and consumer energy efficiency tips.
3c328f29b846e1db	normal	Previously, Rebecca worked at an environmental nonprofit, where she built the organization's digital presence and spearheaded its rebranding efforts.
1d35268d1f45b8cf	normal	U.S. Secretary of the Interior Ryan Zinke announced today that the Laguna Elementary School in New Laguna, New Mexico, will receive twenty-six point two million dollars for the construction of a new school.
2d7c9488a663541b	normal	As Secretary of the Interior, I am responsible for the education of forty eight thousand native children in the Bureau of Indian Education school system​.
7c74c246bb573cd3	normal	That is an honor and responsibility I take very seriously​, said Secretary Zinke.
d162bdb571ea652a	normal	I applaud the Laguna Department Of Education's commitment to providing a first class education to its students​ and for developing a successful plan​.
c6f5c118fdc7418c	normal	An investment in our youth is an investment in our future​.
9e6db168dbe7f1f0	normal	I am hopeful that the proposal President Trump and I put forward to rebuild Indian schools is passed by Congress.
089213a1072995bc	normal	The Pueblo of Laguna is realizing a dream come true with the award to replace the previously condemned Laguna Elementary School, said Laguna Pueblo Governor Virgil Siow.
8babf0b53a599c54	normal	Our Pueblo Administration and Council has worked for many years to obtain funding for a modern, state of the art school to replace the current school.
7c108122e90d6b51	normal	Finally, our children will learn in a safe and modern environment.
dd15f236447bf054	normal	This school will benefit future generations to come.
0f2f20a78e7788aa	normal	The Laguna Elementary School replacement project will support the construction for an education facility serving approximately two hundred twenty students in grades ranging from kindergarten to fifth.
70d5e7eea2f814b2	normal	The school is slated to be built on a forty eight thousand square foot campus.
5a9eadcc82cdeaa6	normal	It includes a Cultural Arts classroom, an additional computer lab, permanent stage space and increased allotments for Special Education therapy and resource classrooms.
1bae67711f1c9b31	normal	The school will be designed for sustainability and is expected to achieve the Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design Silver certification status.
e5c639768dbd53c0	normal	In twenty sixteen, through the No Child Left Behind replacement school construction process, Indian Affairs selected ten schools for replacement.
38e47fb3d4c1c6b3	normal	Laguna Elementary School was the first twenty sixteen School to complete the planning phase.
a44bfc84838359b9	normal	The Pueblo of Laguna has elected to manage the project using a design-build contract for their new school utilizing an amendment to their existing education grant.
382f515740fd1e2a	normal	The United States has the most comprehensive system of assistance for Veterans of any nation in the world, with roots that can be traced back to sixteen thirty-six.
00fc6d502c4d73fc	normal	The Pilgrims of Plymouth Colony were at war with the Pequot Indians.
0c5916de553f4fcc	normal	The Pilgrims passed a law that stated that disabled soldiers would be supported by the colony.
9a864e4b4bd562c5	normal	Later, the Continental Congress of seventeen seventy six encouraged enlistments during the Revolutionary War, providing pensions to disabled soldiers.
f6a04b08f5e91523	normal	In the early days of the Republic, individual states and communities provided direct medical and hospital care to Veterans.
dbcd81bc56af9758	normal	In eighteen eleven, the Federal government authorized the first domiciliary and medical facility for Veterans.
b6dba66bd240d1da	normal	Also in the nineteenth century, the nation's Veterans assistance program was expanded to include benefits and pensions not only for Veterans, but for their widows and dependents.
32b06e71099197e7	normal	Following the Civil War, many state Veterans homes were established.
ee1bfc2031d3c3c8	normal	Since domiciliary care was available at all state Veterans homes, incidental medical and hospital treatment was provided for all injuries and diseases, whether or not of service origin.
655bda9cfa022f41	normal	Indigent and disabled Veterans of the Civil War, Indian Wars, Spanish-American War, and Mexican Border period, as well as the discharged regular members of the Armed Forces, received care at these homes.
30ab9a362170edb8	normal	As the U.S. entered World War One in nineteen seventeen, Congress established a new system of Veterans benefits.
5c1075a759b5b796	normal	This included programs for disability compensation, insurance for service personnel and Veterans, and vocational rehabilitation for the disabled.
5b5a6b27c07ab2d3	normal	By the nineteen twentys, three different federal agencies administered the various benefits: the Veterans Bureau, the Bureau of Pensions of the Interior Department, and the National Home for Disabled Volunteer Soldiers.
906c09229cfa90a8	normal	The first consolidation of federal Veterans programs took place August nine, nineteen twenty one, when Congress combined all World War One Veterans programs to create the Veterans Bureau.
5124088a6b85a9a4	normal	Public Health Service Veterans' hospitals were transferred to the bureau, and an ambitious hospital construction program for World War One Veterans commenced.
e484076238cd5386	normal	World War One was the first fully mechanized war, and as a result, soldiers who were exposed to mustard gas, other chemicals and fumes required specialized care after the war.
facd255df780d4af	normal	Tuberculosis and neuro-psychiatric hospitals opened to accommodate Veterans with respiratory or mental health problems.
31081451bc63cda0	normal	A majority of existing V.A. hospitals and medical centers began as National Home, Public Health Service, or Veterans Bureau hospitals.
1a5b3f095aea276b	normal	In nineteen twenty four, Veterans benefits were liberalized to cover disabilities that were not service-related.
5540c173a0629fc1	normal	In nineteen twenty eight, admission to the National Homes was extended to women, National Guard and militia Veterans.
7cc9c72f15bca622	normal	The second consolidation of federal Veterans programs took place July twenty first, nineteen thirty, when President Herbert Hoover signed Executive Order five thousand three hundred ninety eight and elevated the Veterans Bureau to a federal administration.
ae9beda486266942	normal	The three component agencies became bureaus within the Veterans Administration.
f589a4b6cd44ee4b	normal	Brigadier General Frank T. Hines, who had directed the Veterans Bureau for seven years, was named the first Administrator of Veterans Affairs, a job he held until nineteen forty five.
976c82fbcaa7dab0	normal	Doctor Charles Griffith, V.A.'s second Medical Director, came from the Public Health Service and Veterans Bureau.
80e3cc44975f5021	normal	Both he and Hines were the longest serving executives in V.A.'s history.
ede76a622b840d26	normal	Following World War Two, there was a vast increase in the Veteran population, and Congress enacted large numbers of new benefits for war Veterans—the most significant of which was the World War Two G.I. Bill.
d2539672639175ae	normal	It is said the G.I. Bill had more impact on the American way of life than any law since the Homestead Act of eighteen sixty two.
15ca608828845899	normal	The G.I. Bill placed V.A. second to the War and Navy Departments in funding and personnel priorities.
5fdfb8231e38d663	normal	Modernizing the V.A. for a new generation of Veterans was crucial, and replacement of the "Old Guard" World War One leadership became a necessity.
e0ec8a48ccafba14	normal	The V.A. Home Loan Guaranty Program is the only provision of the original G.I. Bill that is still in force.
cecd30cdd868f427	normal	Between the end of World War Two and nineteen sixty six, one fifth of all single-family residences built were financed by the G.I. Bill for either World War Two or Korean War Veterans.
c4dde7edc7d690ca	normal	From nineteen forty four through December nineteen ninety three, V.A. guaranteed thirteen point nine million home loans valued at more than four hundred thirty three billion dollars.
2a44d1994b3a89eb	normal	Eligible loan guaranty users are now able to negotiate loan terms, including the interest rate, which helps V.A. loan participants to compete better in the housing market.
244861c16074deec	normal	The loan guaranty program no longer has a terminating date and can be used by any Veteran who served after September sixteenth, nineteen forty, as well as men and women on active duty, surviving spouses and reservists.
bff9c9c71630dcc6	normal	To assist the Veteran between discharge and reemployment, the nineteen forty four G.I. Bill also provided unemployment benefits of twenty dollars per week, for a maximum of fifty two weeks.
00a764c351dde719	normal	It was a lesser amount than the unemployment benefits available to non-veterans.
d137ee185f42ad42	normal	This assistance avoided a repetition of the World War One demobilization, when unemployed Veterans were reduced to relying on charities for food and shelter.
918c1e56e34dbf3a	normal	Critics dubbed the benefit the "fifty two-twenty Club" and predicted most Veterans would avoid jobs for the fifty two weeks that the checks were available.
02298254e9608a32	normal	But only a portion of Veterans were paid the maximum amount available.
e719f895515a5327	normal	Less than one-fifth of the potential benefits were claimed, and only one out of nineteen Veterans exhausted the full fifty-two weeks of checks.
ed6580d8969748a7	normal	In nineteen forty-five, General Omar Bradley took the reins at V.A. and steered its transformation into a modern organization.
c8b6c6310776369b	normal	In nineteen forty-six, Public Law two ninety three established the Department of Medicine and Surgery within V.A.
e29e55c3dc225c43	normal	The law enabled V.A. to recruit and retain top medical personnel by modifying the civil service system.
89ec74c4d61e6cb4	normal	When Bradley left in nineteen forty eight, there were one hundred twenty-five V.A. hospitals.
bad0185a92e8fb3f	normal	The V.A. was elevated to a cabinet-level executive department by President Ronald Reagan in October nineteen eighty-eight.
d9008ad8abed42ce	normal	The change took effect March fifteenth, nineteen eighty nine, and administrative changes occurred at all levels.
b6336b7676a5b499	normal	President George H. W. Bush hailed the creation of the new Department, saying, There is only one place for the Veterans of America, in the Cabinet Room, at the table with the President of the United States of America.
e3fb4e747a66c79f	normal	The Veterans Administration was then renamed the Department of Veterans Affairs, and continued to be known as V.A.
450d9ed0ca8ae110	normal	V.A.'s Department of Medicine and Surgery, established in nineteen forty six, was re-designated as the Veterans Health Services and Research Administration at that time.
26b6d03fd15d62b8	normal	On May seventh, nineteen ninety one, the name was changed to the Veterans Health Administration (V.H.A.).
e73ea41b6761f325	normal	V.H.A. evolved from the first federal soldiers' facility established for Civil War Veterans of the Union Army.
cce2bb6313c961b0	normal	On March third, eighteen sixty five - a month before the Civil War ended and the day before his second inauguration - President Abraham Lincoln signed a law to establish a national soldiers and sailors asylum. Renamed as the National Home for Disabled Volunteer Soldiers in eighteen seventy three, it was the first-ever government institution created specifically for honorably discharged volunteer soldiers.
f4b1fb7c2c4596b5	normal	The first national home opened November first, eighteen sixty six, near Augusta, Maine.
22fe511cc99d534c	normal	The national homes were often called "soldiers' homes" or "military homes," and only soldiers who fought for the Union Army, including U.S. Colored Troops, were eligible for admittance.
20fafc0af20b6054	normal	These sprawling campuses became the template for succeeding generations of federal Veterans' hospitals.
a01b8b2c54ed767f	normal	By nineteen twenty-nine, the federal system of national homes had grown to eleven institutions that spanned the country and accepted Veterans of all American wars.
2958c1ee5d790d34	normal	But it was World War One that brought about the establishment of the second largest system of Veterans' hospitals.
f7dceb56a34ee9fe	normal	In nineteen eighteen, Congress tasked two Treasury agencies - the Bureau of War Risk Insurance and Public Health Service - with operating hospitals specifically for returning World War One Veterans.
75967740c6282fff	normal	They leased hundreds of private hospitals and hotels for the rush of returning injured war Veterans and began a program of building new hospitals.
9b946b3bc041de94	normal	Today's V.H.A. - the largest of the three administrations that comprise V.A. - continues to meet Veterans' changing medical, surgical and quality-of-life needs.
0b9bf659c4ea812e	normal	New programs provide treatment for traumatic brain injuries, post-traumatic stress, suicide prevention, women Veterans and more.
9dfbf610433ff17f	normal	V.A. has opened outpatient clinics, and established telemedicine and other services to accommodate a diverse Veteran population, and continues to cultivate ongoing medical research and innovation to improve the lives of America's patriots.
e7283feb77dcf78d	normal	V.H.A. operates one of the largest health care systems in the world and provides training for a majority of America's medical, nursing and allied health professionals.
436b26f6e0564ac2	normal	Roughly sixty percent of all medical residents obtain a portion of their training at V.A. hospitals; and V.A. medical research programs benefit society at-large.
3cffa2ce4ec4b9cf	normal	The V.A. health care system has grown from fifty-four hospitals in nineteen thirty, to include one hundred fifty-two hospitals, eight hundred community-based outpatient clinics, and one hundred twenty-six nursing home care units.
6310bfb0384518a5	normal	On July seventeenth, eighteen sixty two, Congress enacted legislation that authorized the president to purchase "cemetery grounds" to be used as national cemeteries "for soldiers who shall have died in the service of the country."
e7a9f2f09a6afa9e	normal	That first year, fourteen cemeteries were established, including one in the sleepy Maryland town of Sharpsburg, where four thousand four hundred seventy-six Union soldiers were laid to rest following the bloody Battle of Antietam.
35e56692fa042c4d	normal	By eighteen seventy, the remains of nearly three hundred thousand Union dead from the Civil War had been buried in seventy-three national cemeteries.
9dccbee51d087e69	normal	Most of the cemeteries were located in the Southeast, near the battlefields and campgrounds of the Civil War.
3ee667474e124889	normal	After the war, Army crews scoured the countryside to locate the remains of soldiers who had died in battle.
5fef9f8bb3896d8c	normal	They were buried with honor in the new national cemeteries.
5936aa52d7da2241	normal	However, the identities are unknown for nearly half of those who died in service to the Union and are buried in national cemeteries.
52316b6054c0e007	normal	The national cemetery system has evolved slowly since the initial period of great challenge associated with the Civil War.
3c6b5211a8e1ff5b	normal	All honorably discharged Veterans became eligible for burial in eighteen seventy-three.
b151aa724915f498	normal	In the nineteen thirtys, new national cemeteries were established to serve Veterans living in major metropolitan areas such as New York, Baltimore, Minneapolis, San Diego, San Francisco and San Antonio.
691725d24cff443a	normal	Several of them, closely associated with battlefields such as Gettysburg, were transferred to the National Park Service because of the value of their use in interpreting the historical significance of the battles.
97994271d458af89	normal	In nineteen seventy three, Public Law ninety-three forty-three authorized the transfer of eighty-two national cemeteries from the Department of the Army to the Veterans Administration.
4f3d156e0cc7c35f	normal	Joining with twenty-one V.A. Veterans cemeteries located at hospitals and nursing homes, the National Cemetery System comprised one hundred three cemeteries after the transfer.
58e512a3f7405d53	normal	On November eleventh, nineteen ninety eight, the President signed the Veterans Programs Enhancement Act of nineteen ninety eight, changing the name of the National Cemetery System to the National Cemetery Administration.
59410d670440e3e3	normal	Today, there are one hundred thirty-five national cemeteries in all, with new cemeteries in development.
d38d2ed0c43bbad6	normal	Two national cemeteries — Arlington and the United States Soldiers' and Airmen's Home National Cemetery - are still maintained by the Department of the Army.
9c0d2ddc06adf634	normal	Fourteen national cemeteries are maintained by the Department of the Interior.
6fda2f4d0f2d25e2	normal	More than three point five million people, including Veterans of every war and conflict - from the Revolutionary War to the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan - are honored by burial in V.A.'s national cemeteries.
b781da718ee9947c	normal	Today there are more than twenty two million living Veterans who have earned the honor of burial in a national cemetery, including the more than three hundred fifty Medal of Honor recipients.
6fe231fd0458490b	normal	More than twenty one thousand four hundred acres of land are devoted to the memorialization of those who served this nation.
9c0a006381460a07	normal	Do not travel to North Korea due to the serious risk of arrest and long-term detention of U.S. nationals.
a91189c1e609edf3	normal	Individuals cannot use a U.S. passport to travel to, in, or through North Korea without a special validation from the Department of State.
