6b75d46ab66c590c	normal	Teens' Social Media Use: How They Connect and What It Means for Health
42a67847f3a69e7e	normal	In this digital age, technology and the Internet are part of everyday life.
d405225a9007c7f7	normal	Social media platforms such as Instagram, Twitter, and Facebook are especially prominent in the lives of adolescents.
0f2c2e38e158f5f3	normal	They're not just for talking with friends: adolescents use social media to express themselves and find information.
ace1aae0afe2fe4c	normal	Below, we look at their habits, the risks and benefits of social media use, and resources to keep youth safe online.
b9525c548428d8fd	normal	Teen mobile use: seventy five percent of teens can access a smartphone, ninety one percent go online via mobile at least occasionally.
9109716ad1ea7e1b	normal	Ninety four percent of "mobile teens" go online daily.
b5394d1ca4c50f00	normal	The Pew Research Center regularly conducts surveys on technology use in the United States, and collects data on adolescents' social media use.
25c829416f852017	normal	Teens connect via mobile.
379806fe7f3901b3	normal	Widespread and improved mobile technology means teens can access social media more easily.
c6acbbe31ef8d34f	normal	According to a Pew survey conducted during twenty fourteen and twenty fifteen, ninety four percent of teens who go online using a mobile device do so daily.
40dff514971471be	normal	Facebook, Instagram, and Snapchat are the most popular, and seventy one percent of teens say they use more than one social media site.
f624d55d47addf3e	normal	Teens' social media use differs by gender.
bd735a0c10986230	normal	Boys report going on Facebook most often while girls are more likely than boys to use visually-oriented platforms such as Tumblr, Pinterest, and Instagram.
f90c07d93aee2da6	normal	Teens share a lot of their personal information.
9e3a62d24cce5f2b	normal	A survey of over six hundred teens from twenty twelve found that nearly all shared their real name and photos of themselves.
b12cd5f3021ef955	normal	Most shared their school name, birthdate, and the city or town where they lived.
5c26a16e6c33fce2	normal	Teens use social media for romance too.
52ed54dd15963b2b	normal	Another twenty fifteen Pew report on the role of technology notes that half of teens say they've used Facebook or other social networking sites to express romantic interest in someone.
928f001859e47f22	normal	Social Media: Health Resource or Health Risk?
d550e76f0b66b842	normal	As with most technology, there are potential benefits and risks to teens' social media use.
8b4156a3370ccb37	normal	These platforms can help teens socialize and communicate with peers; find learning opportunities; and become engaged in causes important to them.
864c912f24ecc271	normal	Social media also provide a wealth of information and resources that teens can use to maintain their own health and relationships.
7df783ad73e094fb	normal	On the other hand, teens on social media are at risk of cyberbullying and other aggression online; inappropriate content or exposure to predators; and having their private information available publicly.
11942699eec4c80c	normal	There is also some evidence that frequent social media use may be linked to depression and other mental health problems.
37efd6dee8c80146	normal	Ultimately, social media becomes a tool or risk for teen's health based on how they use it, which is in turn shaped by the guidance they get from caring adults.
e3ce96e1be27bd9e	normal	To support teens' healthy social media use, parents and youth-serving professionals can use these resources:
cc6dcf9162e17514	normal	Help teens protect their information online with onguard online dot gov, a federal resource sponsored by the Department of Homeland Security.
1d7466d449585c2a	normal	Talk to teens about being responsible digital citizens.
ccca973d9caf6785	normal	Talk to them about how to prevent and handle issues such as sexting and cyberbullying with additional resources from the Department of Homeland Security's "Stop. Think. Connect." campaign.
0561cc2f27029a33	normal	Set healthy boundaries for social media use with this family media contract example from the American Academy of Pediatrics site for parents.
e108722102db4eda	normal	Check out social media resources from the Department of Health and Human Services and many of its offices for reliable information on adolescent health.
663d2d4614961801	normal	Direct teens toward sites that are designed to help them directly, including the National Runaway Safeline, Smokefree Teen, and the National Suicide Prevention Lifeline.
d4ff14c04470dcca	normal	The broad use of social media by adolescents means it is an influential piece of their lives.
b392504c3a06aa29	normal	Talk with adolescents to help them use social media to support their health.

6a1ea80fcc53c90a	normal	New Mexico Man Sentenced to fifteen Years in Prison for Directing Computer Attacks Against Websites of Dozens of Victims.
18975b1b2c167d4f	normal	A New Mexico man was sentenced today in Saint Paul, Minnesota, for directing computer attacks against the websites of his prior employers, business competitors and public services.
b15942d0693cc95f	normal	Assistant Attorney General John P. Cronan of the Department of Justice's Criminal Division; U.S. Attorney Gregory G. Brooker; and Special Agent Jill Sanborn of the Federal Bureau of Investigation made the announcement.
803bb13b295f14bd	normal	John Kelsey Gammell was sentenced to serve one hundred eighty months in prison by U.S. District Judge Wilhelmina M. Wright of the District of Minnesota.
d86c307c6a7920af	normal	Restitution to the victims of his computer attacks will be determined at a later date.
5e6bf59934bbfdfa	normal	Gammell pleaded guilty on January seventeenth, to one count of conspiracy to cause intentional damage to a protected computer and two counts of being a felon-in-possession of a firearm.
f84a708d684fa718	normal	According to admissions made in connection with his plea, from at least in or about July twenty fifteen through in or about March twenty seventeen, Gammell engaged in a campaign of distributed denial of service attacks on websites throughout the United States.
2d02524ca2ada6cb	normal	A D.D.o.S. attack is a malicious attempt to disable or interrupt service to a computer or website, usually by causing large amounts of Internet traffic to be directed to the computer or website.
4bdccf2b0028e2e0	normal	Gammell directed D.D.o.S. attacks at a number of victims' websites, including websites operated by companies he used to work for, companies that declined to hire him, competitors of his business, and websites for law enforcement agencies and courts, among others.
1a1e1fef4c60a3c7	normal	Gammell purchased subscriptions to multiple D.D.o.S.-for-hire companies.
f2c9ff04e1a6bc1a	normal	He initiated attacks using these companies against dozens of victims, including but not limited to Washburn Computer Group, the Minnesota State Courts, Dakota County Technical College, Minneapolis Community and Technical College, and others.
a1800b5f1dcf4c58	normal	Gammell took a variety of steps to avoid detection and circumvent his victims' attack mitigation efforts.
1e54c7d08b094446	normal	This included using I.P. address anonymization services to mask his identity and location, using cryptocurrency in payment for services, using spoofed emails to conceal his conduct, and using encryption and drive-cleaning tools to conceal digital evidence of his conduct on his computers.
086b172725d3687f	normal	Gammell, who is a convicted felon, also admitted that he possessed parts for use in the building of A.R. fifteen assault rifles.
50323fa173bd69f2	normal	Upper and lower receivers, a pistol grip, a trigger guard, fifteen high-capacity magazines, a buttstock, and four hundred twenty rounds of full metal jacket rifle ammunition.

5a4cd14b4bfa85bd	normal	Trial Attorney Aaron R. Cooper of the Criminal Division's Computer Crime and Intellectual Property Section and Assistant U.S. Attorney Timothy C. Rank of the District of Minnesota are prosecuting the case.
e93e218c0a1f096a	normal	The U.S. Attorney's Offices for the District of Colorado and the District of New Mexico also provided substantial assistance in this matter.

96e438bbe106a63e	normal	Printing, in the only sense with which we are at present concerned, differs from most if not from all the arts and crafts represented in the Exhibition.
62dfea4e8dfdd7f6	normal	The Chinese took impressions from wood blocks engraved in relief for centuries before the woodcutters of the Netherlands.
9665403e472483a6	normal	The invention of movable metal letters in the middle of the fifteenth century may justly be considered as the invention of the art of printing.
77e342eec3225ff2	normal	Printing, then, for our purpose, may be considered as the art of making books by means of movable types.
58dfc27001607c80	normal	All books not primarily intended as picture books consist principally of types composed to form letterpress.
4dcd5d0adf2bc19e	normal	It is of the first importance that the letter used should be fine in form.
675101a131cfa566	normal	No more time is occupied, or cost incurred, in casting, setting, or printing beautiful letters than ugly ones.
e38da2d0c38df4c5	normal	The forms of printed letters should be beautiful, and their arrangement on the page should be a help to the shapeliness of the letters themselves.
f882ab0bb615666f	normal	The Middle Ages brought calligraphy to perfection.
55631cac55f92671	normal	It was natural therefore that the forms of printed letters should follow more or less closely those of the written character, and they followed them very closely.
286aa0e369be1c2c	normal	The first books were printed in black letter, i.e. the letter which was a Gothic development of the ancient Roman character.

b84c248c4614e8e7	normal	On the whole, except in Italy, Gothic letter was most often used.
40cd388832d6fd4b	normal	A few years saw the birth of Roman character not only in Italy, but in Germany and France.
ad9938f307b728a5	normal	In fourteen sixty-five Sweynheim began printing in the monastery of Subiaco near Rome.
8f373a7bd94e3746	normal	He used an exceedingly beautiful type, which is indeed to look at a transition between Gothic and Roman.
f7b76c2c754c1baf	normal	They printed very few books in this type, three only.
8744ad785a0d7d13	normal	They discarded this for a more completely Roman and far less beautiful letter.
1451ef4244af0f99	normal	The Roman type of all these printers is similar in character.
8bbfed77edb19676	normal	It is very simple and legible, and unaffectedly designed for use; but it is by no means without beauty.
08374d4a5e7015ee	normal	A further development of the Roman letter took place at Venice.
80d69f1439003369	normal	John of Spires, followed by Nicholas Jenson, began to print in that city.
b9a00e3a88dc34ba	normal	Their type is on the lines of the German and French rather than of the Roman printers.
45e845280a118755	normal	Of Jenson it must be said that he carried the development of Roman type as far as it can go.

dae59c46b49ef003	normal	As the animal body required to be independent of heat and of the atmosphere, there were no means by which the motion of its fluids could be produced by internal causes.
f6165e39d3e4ff83	normal	Hence arose the second great distinctive character of animals, the circulatory system.
be6073115b746312	normal	Animals further needed muscles for locomotion and nerves for sensibility.
999de4bae36ad948	normal	It was necessary that the chemical composition of the animal body should be more complicated than that of the plant.

ee66e624f3a78de6	normal	The soil and the atmosphere supply plants with water composed of hydrogen and oxygen and carbonic acid containing carbon and oxygen.
38bd73488baf3fdd	normal	They retain the hydrogen and the carbon, exhale the superfluous oxygen and absorb little or no nitrogen.
a3a7705c31267b9a	normal	The essential character of vegetable life is the exhalation of oxygen, which is effected through the agency of light.
f773a93d9cd93cd8	normal	Animals, on the contrary, derive their nourishment either directly or indirectly from plants.

40fa44421f55ff21	normal	That the semi-fluid contents (which we now term protoplasm) of the cells of certain plants are in constant and regular motion was made out a century ago.
414445ac74d18925	normal	But the fact, important as it was, fell into oblivion and had to be rediscovered.

2ff662a10883f400	normal	Touch one of them with the end of a fine human hair and the lobes of the leaf instantly close together.
f05666e4d5337d99	normal	The reflex action of the snail is the result of the presence of a nervous system in the animal.
4d087448faa70eb2	normal	A molecular change takes place in the nerve of the tentacle, is propagated to the muscles by which the body is retracted, and causing them to contract, the act of retraction is brought about.
40a80a9abdcdfb4f	normal	Hence it is conceivable that even the simplest living being may possess a nervous system.

3f0e9518de30c838	normal	So that I know not where we can hope to find any absolute distinction between animals and plants, unless we return to their mode of nutrition.
26260f248cc307c0	normal	A bean may be supplied with water in which salts of ammonia and certain other mineral salts are dissolved in due proportion.
d29cb8b75fac5990	normal	Under these circumstances, unnatural as they are, with proper management, the bean will thrust forth its radicle and its plumule.
3883d4f90e2713f4	normal	The former will grow down into roots, the latter grow up into the stem and leaves of a vigorous bean-plant.
a19912ecdd8bce4f	normal	This plant will, in due time, flower and produce its crop of beans just as if it were grown in the garden or in the field.
18d081e3bc7de091	normal	Nothing has been supplied to the bean save water, carbonic acid, ammonia, potash, lime, iron and the like in combination with phosphoric, sulphuric and other acids.
fc28e1c3d8ab4066	normal	Neither protein, nor fat, nor starch, nor sugar, nor any substance in the slightest degree resembling them has formed part of the food of the bean.
4d11253553f4cb47	normal	The weights of carbon, hydrogen, oxygen, nitrogen, phosphorus, and sulfur contained in the bean plant are exactly equivalent to the weights that have disappeared from the materials supplied.
9c39cf8727fee40c	normal	It follows that the bean has taken in only the raw materials of its fabric and has manufactured them into bean-stuffs.
09afb83ab94f764b	normal	The bean has been able to perform this great chemical feat by the help of its green coloring matter, or chlorophyll.
18b7a3284440f6be	normal	In fact, the bean obtains two of the absolutely indispensable elements of its substance from two distinct sources.
ab0bc27778877d77	normal	The watery solution, in which its roots are plunged, contains nitrogen but no carbon.
a9034dec107d7fb2	normal	The air, to which the leaves are exposed, contains carbon, but its nitrogen is in the state of a free gas, in which condition the bean can make no use of it.
116a1228897703fd	normal	The chlorophyll is the apparatus by which the carbon is extracted from the atmospheric carbonic acid, the leaves being the chief laboratories.

934e89208780e51a	normal	Other measures should be taken as well to improve the overall operation of the Secret Service.
cf09e00749e33db2	normal	Daily supervision of the operations of the Secret Service within the Department of the Treasury should be improved.
038884b517774242	normal	The Chief of the Service now reports to the Secretary of the Treasury.
989fe3a94c48518a	normal	The Department's Employment Policy Program, and who also represents the Secretary of the Treasury on various committees and groups.
b8a1aca9690e87fe	normal	The incumbent has no technical qualifications in the area of Presidential protection.
aba3ec712090049e	normal	The Commission recommends that the Secretary of the Treasury appoint a special assistant with the responsibility of supervising the Service.
a15db315333bb2b9	normal	This special assistant should be required to have sufficient stature and experience in law enforcement, intelligence, or allied fields.
54febd733c77a8b7	normal	To keep the Secretary fully informed regarding all significant developments relating to Presidential protection.
200b71262eea24e6	normal	This report has already pointed out several respects in which the Commission believes that the Secret Service has operated with insufficient planning or control.
80b18d44ab8a31b9	normal	Actions by the Service since the assassination indicate its awareness of the necessity for substantial improvement in its administration.
46d37be311225ee7	normal	A formal and thorough description of the responsibilities of the advance agent is now in preparation by the Service.
b6b8d349ba1af283	normal	Work is going forward.
31436e555f2d9846	normal	The Commission urges that the Service continue this effort to overhaul and define its procedures.
b1c29af72e81057c	normal	While manuals and memoranda are no guarantee of effective operations, no sizable organization can achieve efficiency without the careful analysis.
985984d95c6cc27e	normal	The Commission also recommends that the Secret Service consciously set about the task of inculcating and maintaining the highest standard of excellence, for all of its personnel.
cb6d33c09273258f	normal	This involves tight and unswerving discipline as well as the promotion of an outstanding degree of dedication and loyalty to duty.
949695067cfb1448	normal	The Commission emphasizes that it finds no causal connection between the assassination and the breach of regulations which occurred on the night of November twenty-first at Fort Worth.
0d1029736370ee17	normal	Nevertheless, such a breach is not consistent with the standards which the responsibilities of the Secret Service require it to meet.
a2f1d42e72f68df8	normal	Preventive Intelligence.
008f6a20f53f2879	normal	The Secret Service has largely been the passive recipient of threatening communications to the President.
0ae62018ac0ff43c	normal	This was the consequence of the Service's lack of an adequate investigative staff.
48fe94d862ac8435	normal	The Secret Service has embarked upon a complete overhaul of its research activities.
e294189149675027	normal	The staff of the Protective Research Section has been augmented, and a Secret Service inspector has been put in charge of this operation.
86abb67ac010c6ad	normal	With the assistance of the President's Office of Science and Technology, and of the Advanced Research Projects Agency of the Department of Defense,
6e28878620773391	normal	It has obtained the services of outside consultants, such as the Rand Corporation, I.B.M., and a panel of psychiatric and psychological experts.
c871a7e08b8c3461	normal	It has received assistance also from data processing experts at the C.I.A. and from a specialist in psychiatric prognostication at Walter Reed Hospital.
9b47821404f1f63d	normal	As a result of these studies, the planning document makes several significant recommendations in this field.
574b1adadb06328e	normal	Based on the Commission's investigation, the following minimum goals for improvements are indicated:
2b345e20e20a365c	normal	One: Broader and more selective criteria.
4346485fa84a4373	normal	Since the assassination, both the Secret Service and the F.B.I. have recognized that the P.R.S. files can no longer be limited to persons communicating actual threats to the President.
b7adc96c19f03625	normal	On December twenty-sixth, nineteen sixty-three, the F.B.I. circulated additional instructions to all its agents.
85975bfd896fad8f	normal	They specified criteria for information to be furnished to the Secret Service in addition to that covered by the former standard.
82f59b3173b2eabe	normal	The new instructions require F.B.I. agents to report immediately information concerning subversives, ultrarightists, racists and fascists.
ad9c2716543dae17	normal	Alan H. Belmont, Assistant to the Director of the F.B.I., testified that this revision was initiated by the F.B.I. itself.
9354e6758425a859	normal	The volume of references to the Secret Service has increased substantially since the new instructions went into effect.
ae07b8bee8811f24	normal	More than five thousand names were referred to the Secret Service in the first four months of nineteen sixty-four.
32f643987db75eea	normal	According to Chief Rowley, by mid-June nineteen sixty-four, the Secret Service had received from the F.B.I. some nine thousand reports on members of the Communist Party.
3b28a292f2042406	normal	The F.B.I. now transmits information on all defectors, a category which would, of course, have included Oswald.
231a0f640fcbffea	normal	Both Director Hoover and Belmont expressed to the Commission the great concern of the F.B.I, which is shared by the Secret Service.
064aad07a6615c60	normal	Referrals to the Secret Service under the new criteria might, if not properly handled, result in some degree of interference with the personal liberty of those involved.
bf7b91f14a485ad8	normal	They emphasized the necessity that the information now being furnished be handled with judgment and care.
d6aeb0a650a6d20d	normal	The Commission shares this concern.
78c01f66ad7fad60	normal	The problem is aggravated by the necessity that the Service obtain the assistance of local law enforcement officials in evaluating the information which it receives.
43b99f419070815e	normal	In June nineteen sixty-four, the Secret Service sent guidelines to a number of Federal law enforcement and intelligence agencies
e95c26168e6e1deb	normal	The suggestions of Federal agencies for revision of these guidelines were solicited.
d0c77cfcd0189caa	normal	The new tentative criteria are useful in making clear that the interest of the Secret Service goes beyond information on individuals or groups threatening to cause harm to the President.
06bdbeee90b80e51	normal	Information is requested also concerning individuals or groups who have demonstrated an interest in the President.
ba44a67352b8e38b	normal	Under these criteria, whether the case should be referred to the Secret Service depends on the existence of a previous history of mental instability.
12a921f14a9ebb79	normal	While these tentative criteria are a step in the right direction, they seem unduly restrictive in continuing to require some manifestation of animus against a Government official.
b5edbeaf88c57b60	normal	It is questionable whether such criteria would have resulted in the referral of Oswald to the Secret Service.
427d50ff760892cc	normal	Chief Rowley believed that they would, because of Oswald's demonstrated hostility toward the Secretary of the Navy in his letter.
7ff5fe53e1464c0a	normal	I shall employ all means to right this gross mistake or injustice to a bona fide U.S. citizen and serviceman.
37d14e264bed1b60	normal	The U.S. government has no charges or complaints against me.
2db9aa8986a5dc1b	normal	I ask you to look into this case and take the necessary steps to repair the damage done to me and my family.
3b3b7935b76416fa	normal	Even with the advantage of hindsight, this letter does not appear to express or imply Oswald's determination.
90bbeb9f1efad5ba	normal	It is apparent that a good deal of further consideration and experimentation will be required before adequate criteria can be framed.
68cb7744cc77196c	normal	The Commission recognizes that no set of meaningful criteria will yield the names of all potential assassins.
93760e74dcc11dfd	normal	Each of them was a failure in his work and in his relations with others, a victim of delusions and fancies.
a40ac8319e70883e	normal	It will require every available resource of our Government to devise a practical system which has any reasonable possibility of revealing such malcontents.
650236245e6d7536	normal	Two: Liaison with other agencies regarding intelligence.
ba9480ddbfbb63c9	normal	The Secret Service's liaison with the agencies that supply information to it has been too casual.
e075e4d8139e2cb0	normal	Since the assassination, the Service has recognized that these relationships must be far more formal.
031b3faad8b6aae7	normal	Each agency msut be given a clear understanding of the assistance which the Secret Service expects.
38919b90f591cf05	normal	Once the Secret Service has formulated its new standards for collection of information, it should enter into written agreements with each Federal agency.
41a545c4c6f1e9ed	normal	Such agreements should describe in detail the information which is sought, the manner in which it will be provided to the Secret Service.
830ad9bc4ffba059	normal	This is especially necessary with regard to the F.B.I. and C.I.A.
f9cd6cc7ed9c68bb	normal	They carry the major responsibility for supplying information about potential threats, particularly those arising from organized groups, within their special jurisdiction.
f442477d49286486	normal	Since these agencies are already obliged constantly to evaluate the activities of such groups, they should be responsible for advising the Secret Service.
5ac242f96af3d13f	normal	Detailed formal agreements embodying these arrangements should be worked out between the Secret Service and both of these agencies.
8f5796b9fab9d537	normal	It should be made clear that the Secret Service will in no way seek to duplicate the intelligence and investigative capabilities of the agencies now operating in this field but will continue to use the data developed by these agencies to carry out its special duties.
04d8d7eec07b5202	normal	Once experience has been gained in implementing such agreements with the Federal and leading State and local agencies, the Secret Service, through its field offices, should negotiate similar arrangements with such other State and local law enforcement agencies as may provide meaningful assistance.
895d1f1cdd3d3929	normal	Much useful information will come to the attention of local law enforcement agencies in the regular course of their activities.
df3923694058c638	normal	This source should not be neglected by undue concentration on relationships with other Federal agencies.
dc9c7fc7d74a8cb2	normal	Finally, these agreements with Federal and local authorities will be of little value unless a system is established for the frequent formal review of activities thereunder.
ecdb9a4c6d55bd90	normal	In this regard, the Commission notes with approval several recent measures taken and proposed by the Secret Service to improve its liaison arrangements.
1a1a469275e38132	normal	In his testimony Secretary of the Treasury C. Douglas Dillon informed the Commission that an interagency committee has been established to develop more effective criteria.
b7b9c3de867a8ccf	normal	According to Secretary Dillon, the Committee will include representatives of the President's Office of Science and Technology, Department of Defense, C.I.A., F.B.I, and the Secret Service.
e1cce5d6b6e8ec03	normal	In addition, the Department of the Treasury has requested five additional agents for its Protective Research Section to serve as liaison officers with law enforcement and intelligence agencies.
77bdffca6b0303c8	normal	On the basis of the Department's review during the past several months, Secretary Dillon testified that the use of such liaison officers is the only effective way to insure that adequate liaison is maintained.
3cb167186ee1ae09	normal	As a beginning step to improve liaison with local law enforcement officials, the Secret Service directed its field representatives to send a form request for intelligence information to all local, county, and State law enforcement agencies in their districts.
305369549a44175e	normal	Each of these efforts appears sound, and the Commission recommends that these and the other measures suggested by the Commission be pursued vigorously by Secret Service.
0640a17c2d502083	normal	Three: Automatic data processing
19a555fe71c8c5b8	normal	Unless the Secret Service is able to deal rapidly and accurately with a growing body of data, the increased information supplied by other agencies will be wasted.
1c1af0c8e6f2f509	normal	PRS must develop the capacity to classify its subjects on a more sophisticated basis than the present geographic breakdown.
aa6daf5fe5567936	normal	Its present manual filing system is obsolete;
8e8fa8008a376af2	normal	It makes no use of the recent developments in automatic data processing which are widely used in the business world and in other Government offices.
21f5a2a9f2a7da60	normal	The Secret Service and the Department of the Treasury now recognize this critical need.
d09c8776619d7384	normal	In the planning document currently under review by the Bureau of the Budget, the Department recommends that it be permitted to hire five qualified persons.
849ede64ed466b21	normal	Also the Department requests the sum of one hundred thousand dollars to conduct a detailed feasibility study;
6292fbba09cc6bb8	normal	This money would be used to compensate consultants, to lease standard equipment or to purchase specially designed pilot equipment.
45bb2dc4b5bd08c5	normal	On the basis of such a feasibility study, the Department hopes to design a practical system which will fully meet the needs of the Protective Research Section of the Secret Service.
faab5bd50f0a07cc	normal	The Commission recommends that prompt and favorable consideration be given to this request.
67bb285d4d0bd4fd	normal	The Commission further recommends that the Secret Service coordinate its planning as closely as possible with all of the Federal agencies from which it receives information.
aba95fede9dcf824	normal	The Secret Service should not and does not plan to develop its own intelligence gathering facilities to duplicate the existing facilities of other Federal agencies.
45c1ecf732280e7c	normal	In planning its data processing techniques, the Secret Service should attempt to develop a system compatible with those of the agencies from which most of its data will come.
bc3a05bae880649a	normal	Note: In evaluating data processing techniques of the Secret Service, the Commission had occasion to become informed, to a limited extent, about the data processing techniques of other Federal intelligence and law enforcement agencies.
a06907c373fe39a6	normal	The Commission was struck by the apparent lack of effort, on an interagency basis, to develop coordinated and mutually compatible systems, even where such coordination would not seem inconsistent
2c3b1eeb82af08da	normal	with the particular purposes of the agency involved.
467c99c4cd474380	normal	The Commission recognizes that this is a controversial area and that many strongly held views are advanced in resistance to any suggestion that an effort be made to impose any degree of coordination.
4f84273db1e6b557	normal	This matter is obviously beyond the jurisdiction of the Commission, but it seems to warrant further study before each agency becomes irrevocably committed to separate action.
279f4c962511c9c6	normal	The Commission, therefore, recommends that the President consider ordering an inquiry into the possibility that coordination might be achieved to a greater extent than seems now to be contemplated, without interference with the primary mission of each agency involved.
2bab1337376153ca	normal	Four: Protective Research participation in advance arrangements.
9a52af875b03e9ec	normal	Since the assassination, Secret Service procedures have been changed to require that a member of PRS accompany each advance survey team to establish liaison with local intelligence gathering agencies and to provide for the immediate evaluation of information received from them.
4bff80f2d3f136af	normal	This PRS agent will also be responsible for establishing an informal local liaison committee to make certain that all protective intelligence activities are coordinated.
bf67210e5560f640	normal	Based on its experience during this period, the Secret Service now recommends that additional personnel be made available to PRS so that these arrangements can be made permanent without adversely affecting the operations of the Service's field offices.
43ac8495e5a392ff	normal	The Commission regards this as a most useful innovation and urges that the practice be continued.
54a51bcafd407f3d	normal	Five: Liaison With Local Law Enforcement Agencies.
d28d73f4c5bac4fa	normal	Advice by the Secret Service to local police in metropolitan areas relating to the assistance expected in connection with a Presidential visit has hitherto been handled on an informal basis.
30c61de1e518e35d	normal	The Service should consider preparing formal explanations of the cooperation anticipated during a Presidential visit to a city, in formats that can be communicated to each level of local authorities.
d87db0bcab0995dd	normal	Thus, the local chief of police could be given a master plan, prepared for the occasion, of all protective measures to be taken during the visit.
28a6421fec9bc447	normal	Each patrolman might be given a prepared booklet of instructions explaining what is expected of him.
ed692187450a904f	normal	The Secret Service has expressed concern that written instructions might come into the hands of local newspapers, to the prejudice of the precautions described.
4807893e99eae0c9	normal	However, the instructions must be communicated to the local police in any event and can be leaked to the press whether or not they are in writing.
f1ec414f7c68b331	normal	More importantly, the lack of carefully prepared and carefully transmitted instructions for typical visits to cities can lead to lapses in protection.
7add491fc1e2fb97	normal	Such instructions will not fit all circumstances, of course, and should not be relied upon to the detriment of the imaginative application of judgment in special cases.
41717f4029dcd1ad	normal	Six: Inspection of Buildings
023bcb59b9a57f80	normal	Since the assassination of President Kennedy, the Secret Service has been experimenting with new techniques in the inspection of buildings along a motorcade route.
e7fb6e96772a2c38	normal	According to Secretary Dillon, the studies indicate that there is some utility in attempting to designate certain buildings as involving a higher risk than others.
c28ca4e0ce187bc3	normal	The Commission strongly encourages these efforts to improve protection along a motorcade route.
9b5aee7e347048c2	normal	The Secret Service should utilize the personnel of other Federal law enforcement offices in the locality to assure adequate manpower for this task, as it is now doing.
069d3ecebecbdaf2	normal	Lack of adequate resources is an unacceptable excuse for failing to improve advance precautions in this crucial area of Presidential protection.
0ff779aec3fab2ac	normal	Seven: Secret Service Personnel and Facilities
91e4462e8628687d	normal	Testimony and other evidence before the Commission suggest that the Secret Service is trying to accomplish its job with too few people and without adequate modern equipment.
adb9b8bdc41e5bee	normal	Although Chief Rowley does not complain about the pay scale for Secret Service agents, salaries are below those of the F.B.I. and leading municipal police forces.
bf9a2ec5b2a669dc	normal	The assistant to the Director of the F.B.I. testified that the caseload of each F.B.I. agent averaged twenty to twenty-five, and he felt that this was high.
d67618b6e4406211	normal	Chief Rowley testified that the present workload of each Secret Service agent averages one hundred ten point one cases.
e8dbc3d4f480ac20	normal	While these statistics relate to the activities of Secret Service agents stationed in field offices and not the White House detail, field agents supplement those on the detail, particularly when the President is traveling.
077693f15772c0f9	normal	Although the Commission does not know whether the cases involved are entirely comparable, these figures suggest that the agents of the Secret Service are substantially overworked.
c91e00b3a3f00042	normal	In its budget request, the Secret Service sought funds for twenty-five new positions, primarily in field offices.
36e26b7d654d811e	normal	This increase has been approved by the Congress.
02fcd3b8390ebb02	normal	Chief Rowley explained that this would not provide enough additional manpower to take all the measures which he considers required.
2ab613b680742dce	normal	However, the nineteen sixty-four to sixty-five budget request was submitted in November nineteen sixty-three.
0b65b602fe7ea8de	normal	Reuests for additional personnel were not made because of the studies then being conducted.
83d9054b68e5dee2	normal	The Secret Service has now presented its recommendations to the Bureau of the Budget.
755279fa98881bad	normal	The plan proposed by the Service would take approximately twenty months to implement and require expenditures of approximately three million dollars during that period.
76e23109ca90ea18	normal	The plan provides for an additional two hundred five agents for the Secret Service.
2e6ebf2ea9bdade4	normal	Seventeen of this number are proposed for the Protective Research Section.
166e48b41c96f24e	normal	One hundred forty-five are proposed for the field offices to handle the increased volume of security investigations and be available to protect the President or Vice President when they travel.
4e61030552f46e8a	normal	Eighteen agents are proposed for a rotating pool which will go through an intensive training cycle and also be available to supplement the White House detail in case of unexpected need;
7f5fff30d7ac3d98	normal	And twenty-five additional agents are recommended to provide the Vice President full protection.
785492fdcb937249	normal	The Commission urges that the Bureau of the Budget review these recommendations with the Secret Service and authorize a request for the necessary supplemental appropriation.
409d8007b04f0667	normal	The Congress has often stressed that it will support any reasonable request for funds for the protection of the President.
ae0894663bb1454a	normal	Eight: Manpower and Technical Assistance From Other Agencies
5afb7cf31b430f16	normal	Before the assassination the Secret Service infrequently requested other Federal law enforcement agencies to provide personnel to assist in its protection functions.
484ecfbf51c915d1	normal	Since the assassination, the Service has experimented with the use of agents borrowed for short periods from such agencies.
465af5cf3b1b185a	normal	It has used other Treasury law enforcement agents on special experiments in building and route surveys in places to which the President frequently travels.
d7db2a3d1e005b56	normal	It has also used other Federal law enforcement agents during Presidential visits to cities in which such agents are stationed.
42e254dfba6ce8da	normal	Thus, in the four months following the assassination, the F.B.I, on sixteen separate occasions, supplied a total of one hundred thirty-nine agents to assist in protection work during a Presidential visit.
fca2fc60e9b2e069	normal	From February eleventh through June thirtieth, nineteen sixty-four, the Service had the advantage of nine thousand, five hundred hours of work by other enforcement agencies.
2c3b1dbf80c98430	normal	The F.B.I. has indicated that it is willing to continue to make such assistance available.
02a17976a2d7d26b	normal	The Commission endorses these efforts to supplement the Service's own personnel by obtaining, for short periods of time, the assistance of trained Federal law enforcement officers.
ea884caa8c634c0f	normal	It seems unlikely that the Service could or should increase its own staff to a size which would permit it to provide adequate protective manpower for all situations.
5b86b20fcc9c17f2	normal	The Commission recommends that the agencies involved determine how much periodic assistance they can provide, and that each such agency and the Secret Service enter into a formal agreement defining such arrangements.
5efe535bf9a4c5b1	normal	It may eventually be desirable to codify the practice in an Executive order.
4cd45fdeb706a6a4	normal	The Secret Service will be better able to plan its own long-range personnel requirements if it knows with reasonable certainty the amount of assistance that it can expect from other agencies.
843015d9f78d7f4f	normal	The occasional use of personnel from other Federal agencies to assist in protecting the President has a further advantage.
723bc8bacd472534	normal	It symbolizes the reality that the job of protecting the President has not been and cannot be exclusively the responsibility of the Secret Service.
f2cd2b6931da2024	normal	The Secret Service in the past has sometimes guarded its right to be acknowledged as the sole protector of the Chief Executive.
275d8a9d9322c64f	normal	This no longer appears to be the case.
3476b282adc28d77	normal	Protecting the President is a difficult and complex task which requires full use of the best resources of many parts of our Government.
4994cc7808549e45	normal	Recognition that the responsibility must be shared increases the likelihood that it will be met.
9c43eb8d451c58a3	normal	Much of the Secret Service work requires the development and use of highly sophisticated equipment, some of which must be specially designed to fit unique requirements.
a776b926001857b5	normal	The Secret Service has been receiving full cooperation in scientific research and technological development from many Government agencies including the Department of Defense and the President's Office of Science and Technology.
1268688b558a7c5c	normal	The Commission recommends that the present arrangements with the Office of Science and Technology and the other Federal agencies that have been so helpful to the Secret Service be placed on a permanent and formal basis.
c3d8e9e3bf74405d	normal	The Service should negotiate a memorandum of understanding with each agency that has been assisting it and from which it can expect to need help in the future.
3524bb62d4ac1f6b	normal	The essential terms of such memoranda might well be embodied in an Executive order.
086bc22fb3881249	normal	This Commission can recommend no procedures for the future protection of our Presidents which will guarantee security.
f3be497db448406c	normal	The demands on the President in the execution of His responsibilities in today's world are so varied and complex and the traditions of the office in a democracy such as ours are so deep-seated as to preclude absolute security.
04287d3201119acd	normal	As has been pointed out, the Commission has not resolved all the proposals which could be made.
cbab82349967eafe	normal	The recommendations we have here suggested would greatly advance the security of the office without any impairment of our fundamental liberties.

a516243a76d20c15	normal	Our efforts here should be as strong as they were in combating closed societies during the Cold War.

e937c16c98b8de09	normal	During two thousand, President Bill Clinton and his advisers renewed diplomatic efforts to get Bin Ladin expelled from Afghanistan.
2e2114dab6039112	normal	Though four had training as pilots, most were not well-educated.
c35933fd2293a271	normal	The threat did not receive national media attention comparable to the millennium alert.
4bbd79250b9fa0ec	normal	Domestic agencies were not effectively mobilized.
14f6b9a8897175b9	normal	We have come together with a unity of purpose because our nation demands it.
10afd71754d526ca	normal	Since the plotters were flexible and resourceful, we cannot know whether any single step or series of steps would have defeated them.

1b779ff1937fdd92	normal	Senior military and F.A.A. leaders had no effective communication with each other.
e0e762ec402440d9	normal	In the words of one official, no analytic work foresaw the lightning that could connect the thundercloud to the ground.

c83ee087fd894ed0	normal	We do not believe leaders understood the gravity of the threat.
303d2fe0f3bdf783	normal	No one person can do all these things.

c0301803a1c2319a	normal	This process produces an almost syrupy beverage by extracting both solid and dissolved components.

6798ac341f43c94d	normal	A fungus is any member of the group of organisms that includes yeasts and molds, as well as the more familiar mushrooms.
3115a8e0aec05079	normal	These organisms are classified as a kingdom which is separate from the other eukaryotic kingdoms of plants and animals.
3ddc7d23816de87b	normal	Similar to animals, fungi acquire their food by absorbing dissolved molecules, typically by secreting digestive enzymes into their environment.
1804984ee17a73e3	normal	Fungi do not photosynthesise.
6456bb50b55954a1	normal	Growth is their means of mobility.

04aa0318b9d33735	normal	Abundant worldwide, most fungi are inconspicuous because of the small size of their structures.
f8dd5a9b96888cc0	normal	They may become noticeable when fruiting, either as mushrooms or as molds.
1f33c6d9fdafb03b	normal	Fungi perform an essential role in the decomposition of organic matter.
718309abdf9557cc	normal	They have fundamental roles in nutrient cycling and exchange in the environment.

d6e405c2e3a84f6a	normal	They are used in the fermentation of various food products, such as wine, beer, and soy sauce.
e4263183d734848f	normal	Fungi have been used for the production of antibiotics, and, more recently, various enzymes produced by fungi are used in detergents.
cc92718d1b223299	normal	They are also used as biological pesticides to control weeds, plant diseases and insect pests.

83865e7c71a572bf	normal	In astronomy, the geocentric model is a description of the universe with Earth at the center.
8b278517e5dad6b4	normal	Under the geocentric model, the Sun, Moon, stars, and planets all orbited Earth.
19ebe97e87b2bc76	normal	The geocentric model served as the predominant description of the cosmos in many ancient civilizations.
15062284fc61c780	normal	Modern geocentrism is pseudoscientific.
29b5cc16a8865bad	normal	Two observations supported the idea that Earth was the center of the Universe.
e56ecaf954f32cd8	normal	First, from the view on Earth, the Sun appears to revolve around the Earth once per day.
0c95659d39da1010	normal	The stars appeared to be on a celestial sphere, rotating once each day along an axis through the north and south geographic poles of Earth.
3ecdd063d3b10ac1	normal	Second, Earth does not seem to move from the perspective of an Earth-bound observer; it appears to be solid, stable, and unmoving.
1b8ad8c1bad6733e	normal	The geocentric model entered Greek astronomy and philosophy at an early point; it can be found in pre-Socratic philosophy.

e2363faae83e4f2f	normal	Later these views were combined, so most educated Greeks from the fourth century B.C. on thought that the Earth was a sphere at the center of the universe.
